1
00:00:05,760 --> 00:00:07,400
Hello, everyone.

2
00:00:07,400 --> 00:00:12,680
And welcome to
lecture 7 of CME 295.

3
00:00:12,680 --> 00:00:19,320
So today, we're going to
focus on practical techniques

4
00:00:19,320 --> 00:00:23,600
to let our LLM interact
with the outside world

5
00:00:23,600 --> 00:00:25,840
with other systems.

6
00:00:25,840 --> 00:00:30,840
Because up until now, our
LLM was purely on its own.

7
00:00:30,840 --> 00:00:31,940
We've trained it.

8
00:00:31,940 --> 00:00:36,480
We've seen how it can reason
on problem math, coding math,

9
00:00:36,480 --> 00:00:38,040
coding problems.

10
00:00:38,040 --> 00:00:43,000
And now, what we want to do is
to use our LLM in the context

11
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:45,040
of other systems.

12
00:00:45,040 --> 00:00:49,200
So today's class,
we'll focus on RAG,

13
00:00:49,200 --> 00:00:55,520
that you may have heard,
tool calling, and agents.

14
00:00:55,520 --> 00:00:58,360
But before we
start, as usual, I'm

15
00:00:58,360 --> 00:01:02,020
going to recap what
we did last time.

16
00:01:02,020 --> 00:01:07,740
So if you remember, last time,
we focused on reasoning models.

17
00:01:07,740 --> 00:01:11,660
And we saw the differences
between reasoning model

18
00:01:11,660 --> 00:01:14,820
and what we call
the vanilla LLM.

19
00:01:14,820 --> 00:01:20,500
And in particular, up until the
lecture before last lecture,

20
00:01:20,500 --> 00:01:24,780
what we saw was we fed
a prompt to the LLM,

21
00:01:24,780 --> 00:01:27,740
and it gave us
directly a response.

22
00:01:27,740 --> 00:01:32,260
But what we saw last time
was that if we let the LLM

23
00:01:32,260 --> 00:01:36,420
reason before
outputting the response,

24
00:01:36,420 --> 00:01:39,500
then we can gain
some performance

25
00:01:39,500 --> 00:01:43,980
when it comes to reasoning
tasks, such as math and coding.

26
00:01:43,980 --> 00:01:47,540
And so, in particular,
reasoning models, what they do

27
00:01:47,540 --> 00:01:52,380
is they take a prompt as input,
and then what they output

28
00:01:52,380 --> 00:01:56,500
is both a reasoning
chain, which is typically

29
00:01:56,500 --> 00:02:02,110
hidden from the user,
and then a response.

30
00:02:02,110 --> 00:02:06,110
So with that, we
saw how we could

31
00:02:06,110 --> 00:02:09,910
train a model to be more
of a reasoning model.

32
00:02:09,910 --> 00:02:14,630
And in particular, we
saw a core RL algorithm

33
00:02:14,630 --> 00:02:19,150
called GRPO, which stands
for Group Relative Policy

34
00:02:19,150 --> 00:02:20,830
Optimization.

35
00:02:20,830 --> 00:02:23,750
And we saw that
this algorithm had

36
00:02:23,750 --> 00:02:27,910
some differences compared to
the ones that we saw previously.

37
00:02:27,910 --> 00:02:31,270
And in particular,
one notable aspect

38
00:02:31,270 --> 00:02:33,430
is that it does not have--

39
00:02:33,430 --> 00:02:37,950
it does not train
a value function.

40
00:02:37,950 --> 00:02:41,550
So here, this illustration
shows a little bit

41
00:02:41,550 --> 00:02:43,790
how GRPO is trained.

42
00:02:43,790 --> 00:02:46,830
So it takes a query as input.

43
00:02:46,830 --> 00:02:51,790
And then it computes an
advantage for each output

44
00:02:51,790 --> 00:02:56,610
by computing the rewards
for different completions

45
00:02:56,610 --> 00:02:58,290
of a same prompt.

46
00:02:58,290 --> 00:03:00,450
And then computing
a quantity, which

47
00:03:00,450 --> 00:03:05,290
is the advantage, that is
relative to the other rewards

48
00:03:05,290 --> 00:03:09,450
of that group of completions.

49
00:03:09,450 --> 00:03:12,730
And then we saw
that if we applied

50
00:03:12,730 --> 00:03:17,210
GRPO with carefully
chosen rewards, which

51
00:03:17,210 --> 00:03:23,890
is one, rewarding the model for
outputting a reasoning chain,

52
00:03:23,890 --> 00:03:27,370
and then second,
rewarding the model

53
00:03:27,370 --> 00:03:29,690
for producing a good response.

54
00:03:29,690 --> 00:03:34,730
What we saw is that as the
RL training progresses,

55
00:03:34,730 --> 00:03:40,330
we have an improvement of the
model on these reasoning tasks.

56
00:03:40,330 --> 00:03:45,190
And so we saw one of the
tasks being math problems.

57
00:03:45,190 --> 00:03:49,330
So here on the left graph,
you see the evolution

58
00:03:49,330 --> 00:03:53,430
of the performance of the model
on the aim data set, which

59
00:03:53,430 --> 00:03:58,150
is a challenging math problem.

60
00:03:58,150 --> 00:04:04,710
And we saw that, but we
also saw that the model

61
00:04:04,710 --> 00:04:10,950
kept on outputting responses
that were longer and longer.

62
00:04:10,950 --> 00:04:13,230
And in particular,
we saw that even

63
00:04:13,230 --> 00:04:17,390
though towards the end
of the graph above,

64
00:04:17,390 --> 00:04:19,950
that the performance
was plateauing.

65
00:04:19,950 --> 00:04:27,070
We saw that the output
length was still increasing.

66
00:04:27,070 --> 00:04:32,190
So then what we did was go back
to the loss formulation that

67
00:04:32,190 --> 00:04:36,590
is used by GRPO and
realize that there

68
00:04:36,590 --> 00:04:40,470
is a term that makes
the contribution

69
00:04:40,470 --> 00:04:46,550
of a token different, if
it is in a short response

70
00:04:46,550 --> 00:04:49,190
or a long response.

71
00:04:49,190 --> 00:04:53,160
So this is a phenomenon
called length bias.

72
00:04:53,160 --> 00:04:56,440
And we saw some
mitigation strategies

73
00:04:56,440 --> 00:04:59,960
that were explored by
some papers that came out

74
00:04:59,960 --> 00:05:01,480
in the past few months.

75
00:05:01,480 --> 00:05:08,360
So one was DAPO, which had
a normalization factor that

76
00:05:08,360 --> 00:05:12,480
was not dependent on where
the token was located

77
00:05:12,480 --> 00:05:14,800
and which sentence
it was located.

78
00:05:14,800 --> 00:05:19,880
And the other one was this
paper called "GRPO Done Right,"

79
00:05:19,880 --> 00:05:24,220
which actually just removed
the normalization term.

80
00:05:27,120 --> 00:05:29,600
All good on that?

81
00:05:29,600 --> 00:05:30,100
Cool.

82
00:05:30,100 --> 00:05:32,080
So this was last time.

83
00:05:32,080 --> 00:05:34,120
And last time,
what we said right

84
00:05:34,120 --> 00:05:37,120
before starting
the reasoning class

85
00:05:37,120 --> 00:05:43,440
was to enumerate the strengths
and the weaknesses of vanilla

86
00:05:43,440 --> 00:05:45,240
LLMs.

87
00:05:45,240 --> 00:05:49,700
So last lecture was
all about focusing

88
00:05:49,700 --> 00:05:53,060
on how we can improve
the limited reasoning

89
00:05:53,060 --> 00:05:57,020
capabilities of vanilla LLMs.

90
00:05:57,020 --> 00:06:01,620
And in this lecture, what
we will do is two things.

91
00:06:01,620 --> 00:06:11,100
So the first one is see how we
can connect our LLM to the ever

92
00:06:11,100 --> 00:06:15,340
evolving knowledge base,
and, in particular,

93
00:06:15,340 --> 00:06:20,580
see how we can have access
to the latest information.

94
00:06:20,580 --> 00:06:23,500
And then the second
one is how our LLM

95
00:06:23,500 --> 00:06:26,220
can help us perform actions.

96
00:06:26,220 --> 00:06:28,580
And we will see
this with Shervine

97
00:06:28,580 --> 00:06:33,480
with things like tool calling
and agentic workflows.

98
00:06:33,480 --> 00:06:33,980
Cool.

99
00:06:33,980 --> 00:06:38,220
So with that, let's
start with the first one.

100
00:06:38,220 --> 00:06:41,740
And let's start with
this method called RAG,

101
00:06:41,740 --> 00:06:44,500
that you may have heard.

102
00:06:44,500 --> 00:06:51,270
So let's suppose you have a
model that you have trained.

103
00:06:51,270 --> 00:06:55,990
But the problem is that the
pre-training data on which you

104
00:06:55,990 --> 00:07:01,310
have trained your
model is, let's say,

105
00:07:01,310 --> 00:07:04,030
a month ago, let's suppose.

106
00:07:04,030 --> 00:07:06,910
Now, let's suppose you
want to prompt your model

107
00:07:06,910 --> 00:07:10,430
about the winner of
the elections that

108
00:07:10,430 --> 00:07:13,750
happened a couple of weeks ago.

109
00:07:13,750 --> 00:07:17,070
Well, your model will not
be able to respond to you,

110
00:07:17,070 --> 00:07:22,830
or it will output the incorrect
answer because up until now,

111
00:07:22,830 --> 00:07:28,270
our LLM does not have any
link to outside sources.

112
00:07:28,270 --> 00:07:30,630
It only relies on
the knowledge that it

113
00:07:30,630 --> 00:07:32,830
has acquired during training.

114
00:07:32,830 --> 00:07:35,070
So the response
that it will give us

115
00:07:35,070 --> 00:07:38,950
will only be based
on the data that

116
00:07:38,950 --> 00:07:42,230
has been trained up
until the cutoff, which

117
00:07:42,230 --> 00:07:45,110
is a month ago in this example.

118
00:07:45,110 --> 00:07:49,410
And so we have this big
limitation, which is our LLM

119
00:07:49,410 --> 00:07:53,930
only knows about things
that it has been trained on.

120
00:07:53,930 --> 00:07:57,650
And you will see that
all the models out there.

121
00:07:57,650 --> 00:08:02,730
So here, I have an
example with OpenAI GPT-5

122
00:08:02,730 --> 00:08:05,170
So if you look at
their model cards,

123
00:08:05,170 --> 00:08:08,810
they always have these
knowledge cutoff dates

124
00:08:08,810 --> 00:08:10,690
that is written somewhere.

125
00:08:10,690 --> 00:08:13,570
And in the case, for
instance of GPT-5,

126
00:08:13,570 --> 00:08:19,570
the knowledge cutoff date
is September 30, 2024,

127
00:08:19,570 --> 00:08:23,730
which means that if you ask it
in a very naive way, anything

128
00:08:23,730 --> 00:08:27,250
that happened after that,
the base model will not

129
00:08:27,250 --> 00:08:30,570
be able to answer you as is.

130
00:08:30,570 --> 00:08:34,530
Well, you may tell
me why not just

131
00:08:34,530 --> 00:08:40,575
continue training your model on
data that happened after that?

132
00:08:40,575 --> 00:08:42,450
Well, the problem with
that-- actually, there

133
00:08:42,450 --> 00:08:44,750
are several problems with this.

134
00:08:44,750 --> 00:08:49,310
So the first problem is
that it's very tricky

135
00:08:49,310 --> 00:08:52,670
to change the
knowledge of an LLM

136
00:08:52,670 --> 00:08:55,710
without causing regression
on other things.

137
00:08:55,710 --> 00:09:01,310
So this is typically a task that
people, they try to avoid doing.

138
00:09:01,310 --> 00:09:04,550
And the second thing is
it's not very practical,

139
00:09:04,550 --> 00:09:09,630
because you may very well
have use cases that require

140
00:09:09,630 --> 00:09:12,670
you to fine tune this model.

141
00:09:12,670 --> 00:09:14,590
So let's suppose
you have a use case

142
00:09:14,590 --> 00:09:17,070
one, you fine tune
from this model.

143
00:09:17,070 --> 00:09:21,630
And then somehow you want to
update the weights of your model

144
00:09:21,630 --> 00:09:23,750
to inject some knowledge.

145
00:09:23,750 --> 00:09:28,710
Well, you somehow will have to
do that for all the use cases

146
00:09:28,710 --> 00:09:33,630
that you are doing, which
basically adds a lot of overhead

147
00:09:33,630 --> 00:09:37,990
for you and just adds
a lot of maintenance.

148
00:09:37,990 --> 00:09:43,560
So people, they typically prefer
to not do additional training

149
00:09:43,560 --> 00:09:45,480
to inject knowledge.

150
00:09:45,480 --> 00:09:51,840
So one idea can be to
somehow take your prompt

151
00:09:51,840 --> 00:09:56,600
and just add anything that
happens after the cutoff

152
00:09:56,600 --> 00:10:02,280
date as a way for your model
to just know what happened.

153
00:10:02,280 --> 00:10:06,400
Well, the problem with
that naive approach

154
00:10:06,400 --> 00:10:12,280
is that as you know
context length is limited.

155
00:10:12,280 --> 00:10:15,320
And so typically,
models have on the order

156
00:10:15,320 --> 00:10:20,960
of magnitude of hundreds
of thousands of tokens

157
00:10:20,960 --> 00:10:23,360
in context length.

158
00:10:23,360 --> 00:10:26,480
Do you know what
that is roughly--

159
00:10:26,480 --> 00:10:28,140
what it is roughly equal to?

160
00:10:34,480 --> 00:10:35,200
Yes.

161
00:10:35,200 --> 00:10:37,220
So one token is equal
to four characters.

162
00:10:37,220 --> 00:10:40,740
So using this rough
approximation,

163
00:10:40,740 --> 00:10:44,020
hundreds of thousands
of tokens is roughly

164
00:10:44,020 --> 00:10:47,640
like hundreds of pages,
something like a very big book.

165
00:10:50,890 --> 00:10:53,460
It's big, but it's
not enough for us

166
00:10:53,460 --> 00:10:56,140
to go in that very naive route.

167
00:10:56,140 --> 00:11:02,420
So again, going back to GPT-5,
so if you go to the model card,

168
00:11:02,420 --> 00:11:07,600
you have the knowledge cutoff
date, which is September 2024.

169
00:11:07,600 --> 00:11:09,140
You also have the
context window.

170
00:11:09,140 --> 00:11:15,580
And in this case,
it's 400,000 tokens.

171
00:11:15,580 --> 00:11:19,200
So let's suppose actually,
context is not a problem.

172
00:11:19,200 --> 00:11:21,940
It's actually unlimited.

173
00:11:21,940 --> 00:11:25,380
Let's imagine we actually put
everything in the context.

174
00:11:25,380 --> 00:11:29,740
Well, the problem
then is that people

175
00:11:29,740 --> 00:11:35,420
noticed that if you feed a
lot of irrelevant information

176
00:11:35,420 --> 00:11:41,200
to your LLM, the performance of
the LLM will actually degrade.

177
00:11:41,200 --> 00:11:44,560
Meaning, that if for instance,
you ask it about, I guess,

178
00:11:44,560 --> 00:11:46,760
who was the winner of
the last elections?

179
00:11:46,760 --> 00:11:50,240
And then you feed it
a bunch of information

180
00:11:50,240 --> 00:11:55,070
that are not relevant, your
LLM will tend to be confused.

181
00:11:58,000 --> 00:12:02,320
And so people have
run these tests.

182
00:12:02,320 --> 00:12:09,960
That's called the needle in a
haystack test, where the idea is

183
00:12:09,960 --> 00:12:16,840
you give a big prompt to your
LLM, which is your haystack,

184
00:12:16,840 --> 00:12:22,800
and you place a
fact in the prompt.

185
00:12:22,800 --> 00:12:26,120
And you ask your model
what that fact was.

186
00:12:26,120 --> 00:12:30,460
So the idea is for
your LLM to know,

187
00:12:30,460 --> 00:12:34,560
I guess, among that
huge prompt, where

188
00:12:34,560 --> 00:12:37,970
is the relevant information,
which is the needle.

189
00:12:37,970 --> 00:12:40,410
And so when people
have tried doing

190
00:12:40,410 --> 00:12:44,290
this for several
length of prompts

191
00:12:44,290 --> 00:12:49,210
and tried different positions
of where to put the facts,

192
00:12:49,210 --> 00:12:54,690
they have seen that the length
of the prompt and the position

193
00:12:54,690 --> 00:12:59,770
at which you put the
facts are both important.

194
00:12:59,770 --> 00:13:04,410
So here on the slide,
we have a heat map

195
00:13:04,410 --> 00:13:08,530
that was performed for
GPT-4, which was I guess one

196
00:13:08,530 --> 00:13:10,210
or two years ago.

197
00:13:10,210 --> 00:13:13,530
And what the person
did was placed the fact

198
00:13:13,530 --> 00:13:15,550
at different places
in the document.

199
00:13:15,550 --> 00:13:18,890
So this is document
depth, and the x-axis

200
00:13:18,890 --> 00:13:22,850
is the length of your prompt.

201
00:13:22,850 --> 00:13:25,850
And what we saw was
that for prompts that

202
00:13:25,850 --> 00:13:28,650
exceeded a certain
amount of tokens,

203
00:13:28,650 --> 00:13:33,010
the LLM actually had trouble
retrieving the correct piece

204
00:13:33,010 --> 00:13:35,230
of information.

205
00:13:35,230 --> 00:13:37,790
And in particular, it
had trouble doing so

206
00:13:37,790 --> 00:13:44,310
when the fact was somewhere in
the first half of the prompt.

207
00:13:44,310 --> 00:13:49,030
So this just tells us that,
even if, let's say, our context

208
00:13:49,030 --> 00:13:51,990
length was unlimited,
we would still

209
00:13:51,990 --> 00:13:57,310
have a problem by just going
through that naive approach.

210
00:13:57,310 --> 00:13:59,150
So that's another reason.

211
00:13:59,150 --> 00:14:03,590
So now, let's suppose,
context length is unlimited.

212
00:14:03,590 --> 00:14:07,870
Let's suppose the problem that
I mentioned is not a problem.

213
00:14:07,870 --> 00:14:13,190
Well, the other problem
is that you pay.

214
00:14:13,190 --> 00:14:17,750
So in particular, these
calls, these LLM calls,

215
00:14:17,750 --> 00:14:20,030
they are per token.

216
00:14:20,030 --> 00:14:25,150
So the bigger your input
prompt, the more you will pay.

217
00:14:25,150 --> 00:14:30,870
So you have an incentive to not
put too much in your prompt just

218
00:14:30,870 --> 00:14:33,090
from that standpoint.

219
00:14:33,090 --> 00:14:37,090
And so for instance,
again, going back to GPT-5,

220
00:14:37,090 --> 00:14:43,210
order of magnitude is somewhere
around $1 per million token.

221
00:14:43,210 --> 00:14:45,350
So I guess it's
not that expensive,

222
00:14:45,350 --> 00:14:50,050
but it can add up, if you do
that for all your prompts.

223
00:14:50,050 --> 00:14:53,610
So for all these reasons,
I hope I convinced you

224
00:14:53,610 --> 00:14:58,330
that we need a more
clever approach, where

225
00:14:58,330 --> 00:15:02,610
instead of putting all the
new information all at once

226
00:15:02,610 --> 00:15:07,130
in the prompt, what we
do is we only somehow

227
00:15:07,130 --> 00:15:13,690
find the relevant information
and put that in the prompt.

228
00:15:13,690 --> 00:15:16,850
So that is the idea behind RAG.

229
00:15:16,850 --> 00:15:22,450
RAG stands for Retrieval
Augmented Generation.

230
00:15:22,450 --> 00:15:28,450
And the idea here is to augment
the prompt with relevant

231
00:15:28,450 --> 00:15:30,540
information.

232
00:15:30,540 --> 00:15:34,900
And here, I put
relevant in bold.

233
00:15:34,900 --> 00:15:37,580
And this is the, I guess, the
core part of this technique

234
00:15:37,580 --> 00:15:42,140
is how can we get only the
relevant part in the prompt?

235
00:15:42,140 --> 00:15:44,420
So we'll see that in a second.

236
00:15:44,420 --> 00:15:47,700
So just at a very high
level, so you have,

237
00:15:47,700 --> 00:15:49,920
let's say, a question as input.

238
00:15:49,920 --> 00:15:53,740
So in this case, who was
the winner of, let's say,

239
00:15:53,740 --> 00:15:56,700
the local election?

240
00:15:56,700 --> 00:16:00,780
The idea here is
to somehow fetch

241
00:16:00,780 --> 00:16:04,180
the correct or the relevant
piece of information

242
00:16:04,180 --> 00:16:08,490
and then augment that here in
order to output your answer.

243
00:16:11,180 --> 00:16:14,780
So that's the rough idea.

244
00:16:14,780 --> 00:16:19,820
So does this method
make sense so far?

245
00:16:19,820 --> 00:16:21,120
Yeah.

246
00:16:21,120 --> 00:16:21,620
OK.

247
00:16:21,620 --> 00:16:22,140
Cool.

248
00:16:22,140 --> 00:16:24,700
So that is the idea behind RAG.

249
00:16:24,700 --> 00:16:28,800
And now, we're going to
go into more details.

250
00:16:28,800 --> 00:16:31,640
So what I mentioned
is the rough idea.

251
00:16:31,640 --> 00:16:34,240
And here, I just
want to emphasize

252
00:16:34,240 --> 00:16:36,800
on the three main steps of RAG.

253
00:16:36,800 --> 00:16:40,240
So first one is you
have your prompt,

254
00:16:40,240 --> 00:16:45,680
and you somehow want to retrieve
a relevant piece of information

255
00:16:45,680 --> 00:16:48,920
that will help you in
answering your prompt.

256
00:16:48,920 --> 00:16:53,880
So here, the first step is to
retrieve relevant documents.

257
00:16:53,880 --> 00:16:57,320
And so you can think of your
prompt as being one entity.

258
00:16:57,320 --> 00:17:02,080
And then you can have some
other space, which maybe, I

259
00:17:02,080 --> 00:17:06,839
don't know, knowledge base,
where all your documents live.

260
00:17:06,839 --> 00:17:12,079
And so the idea is to somehow
fetch the relevant documents.

261
00:17:12,079 --> 00:17:14,160
So this is the retrieve step.

262
00:17:14,160 --> 00:17:16,839
The second step is
once you have fetched

263
00:17:16,839 --> 00:17:21,040
the relevant information,
you augment your prompt.

264
00:17:21,040 --> 00:17:24,140
So you take that retrieved info.

265
00:17:24,140 --> 00:17:28,109
You just put it in your prompt,
and then ask the question.

266
00:17:28,109 --> 00:17:31,010
So in the local
election example,

267
00:17:31,010 --> 00:17:35,890
it's as if I was saying, who
is the winner of this election?

268
00:17:35,890 --> 00:17:39,670
And then I retrieve the
relevant piece of information.

269
00:17:39,670 --> 00:17:44,670
And now, the prompt becomes, who
is the winner of this election?

270
00:17:44,670 --> 00:17:47,990
And by the way, this election
was held, blah, blah, blah.

271
00:17:47,990 --> 00:17:49,810
And this was the winner.

272
00:17:49,810 --> 00:17:53,530
And this is what we're
feeding to our LLM.

273
00:17:53,530 --> 00:17:59,490
So in other words, we're giving
the answer in the prompt.

274
00:17:59,490 --> 00:18:05,130
And the third step is to
feed that prompt to the LLM

275
00:18:05,130 --> 00:18:06,630
to generate the response.

276
00:18:06,630 --> 00:18:07,130
Yeah?

277
00:18:20,570 --> 00:18:21,110
Exactly.

278
00:18:21,110 --> 00:18:24,590
So the question is, you
may very well somehow

279
00:18:24,590 --> 00:18:28,150
do a bad job at
retrieval stage, so yes.

280
00:18:28,150 --> 00:18:31,550
So this is why the retrieval
stage is so important.

281
00:18:31,550 --> 00:18:35,070
And we're going to focus on
what we can do to make sure

282
00:18:35,070 --> 00:18:37,330
that one part does well.

283
00:18:41,550 --> 00:18:45,490
We'll see how we can
evaluate, I guess,

284
00:18:45,490 --> 00:18:48,090
our setup and different methods.

285
00:18:48,090 --> 00:18:50,550
But when we talk
about RAG, we're

286
00:18:50,550 --> 00:18:53,350
mainly focusing on
making the retrieval

287
00:18:53,350 --> 00:18:57,950
parts as good as it can.

288
00:18:57,950 --> 00:18:58,550
Cool.

289
00:18:58,550 --> 00:19:02,190
And I just want to
emphasize once again

290
00:19:02,190 --> 00:19:04,710
on why it's called RAG.

291
00:19:04,710 --> 00:19:11,110
So you have retrieve,
augment, generate--

292
00:19:11,110 --> 00:19:13,350
RAG.

293
00:19:13,350 --> 00:19:13,990
Cool.

294
00:19:13,990 --> 00:19:16,890
And as you pointed
out, the first step,

295
00:19:16,890 --> 00:19:19,970
which is the retrieval
step is very important,

296
00:19:19,970 --> 00:19:24,930
which is why we'll spend a
little bit of time over there.

297
00:19:24,930 --> 00:19:29,490
So I guess the
first step is for us

298
00:19:29,490 --> 00:19:37,730
to somehow clean the set of
documents that we may need.

299
00:19:37,730 --> 00:19:43,550
So I said, we may want to
look into outside information,

300
00:19:43,550 --> 00:19:48,730
but we need to somehow sort that
order that put that somewhere.

301
00:19:48,730 --> 00:19:53,890
And this whole thing is usually
called a knowledge base.

302
00:19:53,890 --> 00:19:56,890
So in order to form
our knowledge base,

303
00:19:56,890 --> 00:20:00,730
what we do is typically
collect the set of documents

304
00:20:00,730 --> 00:20:04,810
that are or may be useful.

305
00:20:04,810 --> 00:20:08,610
And once we do that, what
we do is we divide them

306
00:20:08,610 --> 00:20:12,250
into, what we call, chunks.

307
00:20:12,250 --> 00:20:15,050
So a chunk is you
can think of it

308
00:20:15,050 --> 00:20:18,650
as a subset of
the document which

309
00:20:18,650 --> 00:20:22,260
has a given maximum
length, which is

310
00:20:22,260 --> 00:20:25,580
are measured in number of
tokens, which is typically

311
00:20:25,580 --> 00:20:29,180
on the order of
hundreds of tokens.

312
00:20:29,180 --> 00:20:34,500
And the idea here is
whenever you hear retrieval,

313
00:20:34,500 --> 00:20:37,260
you should think
about embeddings.

314
00:20:37,260 --> 00:20:43,260
And here, what we do is we
compute embeddings corresponding

315
00:20:43,260 --> 00:20:46,660
to each of these chunks.

316
00:20:46,660 --> 00:20:50,020
Now, when you create
your knowledge base,

317
00:20:50,020 --> 00:20:54,020
there are a few hyperparameters
that you need to tweak.

318
00:20:54,020 --> 00:20:59,060
So the first one, obviously,
is the size of the embedding.

319
00:20:59,060 --> 00:21:02,020
So typically, you would
want a bigger size,

320
00:21:02,020 --> 00:21:03,900
if, let's say, your
documents are maybe

321
00:21:03,900 --> 00:21:07,460
more nuanced, more complex.

322
00:21:07,460 --> 00:21:10,300
But then if you
have a higher size,

323
00:21:10,300 --> 00:21:12,720
maybe it will take more space.

324
00:21:12,720 --> 00:21:15,000
Maybe you'll have more
computation at inference time.

325
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:16,320
So I guess it's a trade-off.

326
00:21:16,320 --> 00:21:20,640
You don't necessarily want
too big of an embedding size.

327
00:21:20,640 --> 00:21:23,160
So here, typically,
embedding sizes

328
00:21:23,160 --> 00:21:25,780
are on the order of thousands.

329
00:21:25,780 --> 00:21:30,520
So for instance, like
1,500 something like this.

330
00:21:30,520 --> 00:21:32,440
So then you have the chunk size.

331
00:21:32,440 --> 00:21:39,120
Chunk size is how big your
little pieces here are.

332
00:21:39,120 --> 00:21:42,760
So you don't want them to be
too small, because, otherwise,

333
00:21:42,760 --> 00:21:45,840
the text may be out of context.

334
00:21:45,840 --> 00:21:47,500
You don't want it
to be too large,

335
00:21:47,500 --> 00:21:50,480
because maybe the embedding
will not represent,

336
00:21:50,480 --> 00:21:52,920
in a meaningful
way, what is inside.

337
00:21:52,920 --> 00:21:55,080
So again, it's a trade-off.

338
00:21:55,080 --> 00:21:57,880
But typically,
people they choose

339
00:21:57,880 --> 00:22:01,600
chunk size of around 500
tokens, like, on the order

340
00:22:01,600 --> 00:22:05,040
of hundreds of tokens.

341
00:22:05,040 --> 00:22:07,180
And then you also
have a-- oh yeah.

342
00:22:07,180 --> 00:22:08,400
You have a question.

343
00:22:08,400 --> 00:22:10,880
Yeah?

344
00:22:10,880 --> 00:22:13,740
So the question is, do you train
an embedding model for this.

345
00:22:13,740 --> 00:22:16,000
So you have two
choices, either you

346
00:22:16,000 --> 00:22:20,140
can use a pre-trained embedding
model, which people typically

347
00:22:20,140 --> 00:22:23,860
do, or you can train your own.

348
00:22:23,860 --> 00:22:26,830
We will see that in a bit
more detail in a few slides.

349
00:22:34,100 --> 00:22:37,000
So the question is, what is the
purpose of the embedding model?

350
00:22:37,000 --> 00:22:38,480
So we will see this in a second.

351
00:22:38,480 --> 00:22:45,020
But long story short, it
tries to represent chunks,

352
00:22:45,020 --> 00:22:48,120
such that it achieves
your end goal,

353
00:22:48,120 --> 00:22:52,440
which is to fetch
relevant documents.

354
00:22:52,440 --> 00:22:54,440
So we will see a little
bit how they're trained.

355
00:22:54,440 --> 00:22:55,990
But this is the general idea.

356
00:22:58,500 --> 00:22:59,960
Cool.

357
00:22:59,960 --> 00:23:00,720
So that's this.

358
00:23:00,720 --> 00:23:04,420
And then we have a
third hyperparameter,

359
00:23:04,420 --> 00:23:07,500
which is how much
overlap you want

360
00:23:07,500 --> 00:23:11,020
to have in between your chunks.

361
00:23:11,020 --> 00:23:17,690
So here, when you do the
division, in a very naive way,

362
00:23:17,690 --> 00:23:20,030
you have everything be
independent, no overlap

363
00:23:20,030 --> 00:23:21,150
in between.

364
00:23:21,150 --> 00:23:24,350
But typically,
you have some part

365
00:23:24,350 --> 00:23:26,190
that is from the
previous chunk that

366
00:23:26,190 --> 00:23:29,630
is relevant to understand
the current chunk, which

367
00:23:29,630 --> 00:23:32,870
is why we want to have
some overlap, which

368
00:23:32,870 --> 00:23:35,530
is why people, they
typically also have that.

369
00:23:35,530 --> 00:23:38,800
So it's typically in the
low hundreds of tokens.

370
00:23:41,870 --> 00:23:42,770
Cool.

371
00:23:42,770 --> 00:23:45,670
So let's suppose you
have your knowledge base.

372
00:23:45,670 --> 00:23:49,470
Now, the question
is, given a prompt,

373
00:23:49,470 --> 00:23:53,790
how can you retrieve
relevant documents?

374
00:23:53,790 --> 00:23:59,990
And the answer to that is we
typically proceed in two steps.

375
00:23:59,990 --> 00:24:02,270
So I'm not sure
if any of you has

376
00:24:02,270 --> 00:24:07,070
a background in recommendation
systems or search.

377
00:24:07,070 --> 00:24:07,650
Does any?

378
00:24:07,650 --> 00:24:08,710
Yeah.

379
00:24:08,710 --> 00:24:12,370
So the methods we're seeing here
are very similar to that space.

380
00:24:12,370 --> 00:24:15,590
So I guess people in
the LLM community.

381
00:24:15,590 --> 00:24:19,410
They have borrowed ideas and
just leveraged some techniques

382
00:24:19,410 --> 00:24:20,850
that we have over there.

383
00:24:20,850 --> 00:24:24,530
And this is typically, a
setting that will also have

384
00:24:24,530 --> 00:24:27,210
for recommendation problems.

385
00:24:27,210 --> 00:24:29,770
So we have two stages.

386
00:24:29,770 --> 00:24:35,730
So the first stage is typically
called candidate retrieval.

387
00:24:35,730 --> 00:24:38,850
And the goal here
is to go from a set

388
00:24:38,850 --> 00:24:43,530
of many, many, many
chunks, and filter it down

389
00:24:43,530 --> 00:24:49,650
to a much smaller set of
potentially relevant candidates.

390
00:24:49,650 --> 00:24:51,970
So during that stage,
what we're trying to do

391
00:24:51,970 --> 00:24:58,130
is to somehow maximize recall,
just do a rough operation,

392
00:24:58,130 --> 00:25:02,450
so that we get as many
potentially relevant candidates

393
00:25:02,450 --> 00:25:04,690
as possible.

394
00:25:04,690 --> 00:25:09,850
And then we have a second stage,
which is sometimes optional.

395
00:25:09,850 --> 00:25:15,350
But this stage is to really make
sure we have the top documents

396
00:25:15,350 --> 00:25:17,750
being really the relevant ones.

397
00:25:17,750 --> 00:25:21,190
And this one is called ranking.

398
00:25:21,190 --> 00:25:27,590
So the idea here is based on
the list of potentially relevant

399
00:25:27,590 --> 00:25:30,830
documents, to really
rank them in a way

400
00:25:30,830 --> 00:25:36,630
that really the relevant ones
come at the top and so on.

401
00:25:36,630 --> 00:25:38,830
And typically,
during that stage,

402
00:25:38,830 --> 00:25:42,350
we're going to use a
model, a method that's

403
00:25:42,350 --> 00:25:46,350
going to be a bit more compute
intensive because we have

404
00:25:46,350 --> 00:25:50,310
a much smaller set of
candidates to rank compared

405
00:25:50,310 --> 00:25:52,830
to the first one.

406
00:25:52,830 --> 00:25:55,590
So going back to your
question on how do we

407
00:25:55,590 --> 00:25:57,290
want our embeddings to be?

408
00:25:57,290 --> 00:26:00,870
So here, it will really
impact the first stage.

409
00:26:00,870 --> 00:26:02,370
And we will see
that in a second.

410
00:26:02,370 --> 00:26:04,970
But the second stage is
also quite important.

411
00:26:08,440 --> 00:26:09,820
Cool.

412
00:26:09,820 --> 00:26:10,660
So far so good?

413
00:26:10,660 --> 00:26:15,240
Is everyone clear with
the two-stage approach?

414
00:26:15,240 --> 00:26:15,740
Yeah.

415
00:26:27,040 --> 00:26:27,860
Very good question.

416
00:26:27,860 --> 00:26:30,860
So the question is, do we
chunk things in a naive way,

417
00:26:30,860 --> 00:26:33,600
as in we just go with
the number of tokens

418
00:26:33,600 --> 00:26:35,100
regardless of what happens?

419
00:26:35,100 --> 00:26:36,800
So it's a great question.

420
00:26:36,800 --> 00:26:41,840
And the answer is that we
will see some extensions that

421
00:26:41,840 --> 00:26:46,360
will mitigate the problem of
when you chunk it in a way that

422
00:26:46,360 --> 00:26:48,760
does not make sense
in a naive way,

423
00:26:48,760 --> 00:26:51,540
you want to somehow
put that into context.

424
00:26:51,540 --> 00:26:53,680
And we will see a
method that does that.

425
00:26:53,680 --> 00:26:57,415
So in a few slides,
we will see that.

426
00:26:57,415 --> 00:26:59,540
But I think your question
is also a great question,

427
00:26:59,540 --> 00:27:02,440
because depending on the kind
of document that we have,

428
00:27:02,440 --> 00:27:05,720
for instance, if we have,
I don't know, like a JSON

429
00:27:05,720 --> 00:27:10,660
file or a markdown or depending
on the file that you need

430
00:27:10,660 --> 00:27:14,900
to chunk, you also need to be
aware of the structure that

431
00:27:14,900 --> 00:27:16,460
is within those files.

432
00:27:16,460 --> 00:27:18,500
So there is also
some nuance there

433
00:27:18,500 --> 00:27:20,160
that we will not
go into details,

434
00:27:20,160 --> 00:27:23,100
but I just want
to call that out.

435
00:27:23,100 --> 00:27:25,980
But, yeah, great question.

436
00:27:25,980 --> 00:27:29,120
Any other questions?

437
00:27:29,120 --> 00:27:29,620
OK.

438
00:27:29,620 --> 00:27:30,180
Cool.

439
00:27:30,180 --> 00:27:36,900
So now that we're clear on the
two main stages of retrieval,

440
00:27:36,900 --> 00:27:40,380
we're going to focus on
each one of these steps.

441
00:27:40,380 --> 00:27:46,020
So as I mentioned, the first
step is candidate retrieval.

442
00:27:46,020 --> 00:27:51,820
So here, what we want is among
that potentially huge knowledge

443
00:27:51,820 --> 00:27:56,200
base to somehow
filter it down to,

444
00:27:56,200 --> 00:28:02,100
let's say, over 100 potentially
relevant candidates.

445
00:28:02,100 --> 00:28:06,270
So here, what we do is well,
we will leverage the embeddings

446
00:28:06,270 --> 00:28:12,750
that I guess computed during the
knowledge base initialization.

447
00:28:12,750 --> 00:28:20,390
And we will try to fetch
potentially relevant candidates

448
00:28:20,390 --> 00:28:25,390
by doing a semantic
similarity search.

449
00:28:25,390 --> 00:28:28,530
So do you recall how
we compare embeddings?

450
00:28:31,150 --> 00:28:31,990
Yes.

451
00:28:31,990 --> 00:28:33,990
So cosine similarity
is typically

452
00:28:33,990 --> 00:28:36,910
one way one good way
to compare embeddings.

453
00:28:36,910 --> 00:28:43,230
So the idea here is to represent
our query with an embedding.

454
00:28:43,230 --> 00:28:48,110
We already have embeddings
of all our chunks.

455
00:28:48,110 --> 00:28:55,310
So the idea here is to somehow
find the most relevant chunks

456
00:28:55,310 --> 00:29:00,270
by doing this similarity
search and filtering out

457
00:29:00,270 --> 00:29:03,330
the ones that come at the top.

458
00:29:03,330 --> 00:29:07,410
So the idea here is you have
your query, you have your chunk.

459
00:29:07,410 --> 00:29:10,690
both of them, you
find an embedding.

460
00:29:10,690 --> 00:29:13,690
And then you perform a
similarity operation,

461
00:29:13,690 --> 00:29:17,410
which is most of the
time cosine similarity.

462
00:29:17,410 --> 00:29:20,450
And you obtain a
similarity score.

463
00:29:20,450 --> 00:29:26,370
So the idea here is you
just keep top, I don't 100,

464
00:29:26,370 --> 00:29:28,970
and you go with that.

465
00:29:28,970 --> 00:29:31,450
So I just want to
call out that there

466
00:29:31,450 --> 00:29:35,250
is some complexity
in that stage,

467
00:29:35,250 --> 00:29:40,010
because your knowledge base
can potentially be huge.

468
00:29:40,010 --> 00:29:43,610
So what people do
is typically use

469
00:29:43,610 --> 00:29:48,090
what we call approximate
nearest neighbor methods.

470
00:29:48,090 --> 00:29:50,830
So you may have heard of
some libraries that do that.

471
00:29:50,830 --> 00:29:54,570
So typically, this is something
that will be relevant here.

472
00:29:54,570 --> 00:29:56,110
We're not going to
go into details,

473
00:29:56,110 --> 00:29:57,890
but I just want
to call that out.

474
00:29:57,890 --> 00:30:03,350
So here, the idea here is that
when you build your knowledge

475
00:30:03,350 --> 00:30:08,910
base, you somehow
partition the embeddings

476
00:30:08,910 --> 00:30:15,270
in a way that will avoid-- like
make you avoid doing like just

477
00:30:15,270 --> 00:30:18,070
a naive linear search.

478
00:30:18,070 --> 00:30:19,430
So that's the idea.

479
00:30:19,430 --> 00:30:24,090
But you may see some
techniques like ANN techniques,

480
00:30:24,090 --> 00:30:26,630
approximate nearest
neighbor techniques.

481
00:30:26,630 --> 00:30:30,710
And these are typically
happening here.

482
00:30:30,710 --> 00:30:33,990
So another thing that
I want to point out

483
00:30:33,990 --> 00:30:39,590
is the name of the architecture
that we typically use here

484
00:30:39,590 --> 00:30:41,950
that you may also hear.

485
00:30:41,950 --> 00:30:47,270
And for that, we need to
recall that these embeddings,

486
00:30:47,270 --> 00:30:50,650
they're actually obtained by
passing them through a model.

487
00:30:50,650 --> 00:30:53,590
So typically encoder only.

488
00:30:53,590 --> 00:30:58,030
So you may hear the
term BI encoder.

489
00:30:58,030 --> 00:31:01,680
And this one refers
to the fact that we

490
00:31:01,680 --> 00:31:04,840
are passing the query
through an encoder

491
00:31:04,840 --> 00:31:08,060
and then passing the
chunk through an encoder.

492
00:31:08,060 --> 00:31:11,640
So both of them are independent.

493
00:31:11,640 --> 00:31:13,780
And we're comparing
the embeddings.

494
00:31:16,780 --> 00:31:18,780
So this is another question
I wanted to ask you.

495
00:31:18,780 --> 00:31:22,360
But I guess I didn't
get the chance to.

496
00:31:22,360 --> 00:31:26,520
If you remember, I think
lecture two or three,

497
00:31:26,520 --> 00:31:30,680
we had seen the BERT model.

498
00:31:30,680 --> 00:31:35,080
And so typically, you would have
something like a BERT-like model

499
00:31:35,080 --> 00:31:41,440
that you would use to
encode these documents.

500
00:31:41,440 --> 00:31:43,360
So going back to your
question, how do you

501
00:31:43,360 --> 00:31:44,500
compute these embeddings?

502
00:31:44,500 --> 00:31:47,740
So there is a paper that I
highly recommend reading.

503
00:31:47,740 --> 00:31:52,640
Actually, that's
called Sentence BERT.

504
00:31:52,640 --> 00:31:55,000
And so that paper explains--

505
00:31:55,000 --> 00:31:57,360
so it's, first of all,
it's an extension of BERT,

506
00:31:57,360 --> 00:31:59,580
as the name suggests.

507
00:31:59,580 --> 00:32:03,700
And it's an
extension that allows

508
00:32:03,700 --> 00:32:07,720
you to compute an
embedding per, let's say,

509
00:32:07,720 --> 00:32:11,260
sequence for your query,
for your document, that

510
00:32:11,260 --> 00:32:17,980
is tailored to be used for
similarity search purposes.

511
00:32:17,980 --> 00:32:22,180
So the idea here is to
have a loss function that

512
00:32:22,180 --> 00:32:25,300
will incentivize
having a high cosine

513
00:32:25,300 --> 00:32:29,580
similarity for relevant
entities and low cosine

514
00:32:29,580 --> 00:32:34,060
similarity for entities
that are not relevant.

515
00:32:34,060 --> 00:32:37,140
So yeah, so feel free
to check that paper out,

516
00:32:37,140 --> 00:32:39,380
if you know BERT,
which I know right now,

517
00:32:39,380 --> 00:32:42,060
you do, it's quite easy to read.

518
00:32:42,060 --> 00:32:45,340
So highly recommend.

519
00:32:45,340 --> 00:32:47,860
So far so good?

520
00:32:47,860 --> 00:32:48,620
Yeah?

521
00:32:48,620 --> 00:32:49,120
Yeah?

522
00:32:54,380 --> 00:32:56,040
So the question is,
what is the default

523
00:32:56,040 --> 00:32:58,100
way to compute the similarity?

524
00:32:58,100 --> 00:33:00,520
So yes, it's cosine similarity.

525
00:33:00,520 --> 00:33:03,600
But again, you will see in
different implementations

526
00:33:03,600 --> 00:33:06,680
that people can use
other distances.

527
00:33:06,680 --> 00:33:09,800
And I would encourage
you to think about how

528
00:33:09,800 --> 00:33:12,080
they relate to one another.

529
00:33:12,080 --> 00:33:15,520
So you will see, for
instance, the L2 distance.

530
00:33:15,520 --> 00:33:19,560
But then if everything
has a norm of 1,

531
00:33:19,560 --> 00:33:22,320
there's a lot of
simplifications that can happen.

532
00:33:22,320 --> 00:33:24,320
So you may see some
variants, but I

533
00:33:24,320 --> 00:33:29,040
would say they're all more
or less cosine similarities.

534
00:33:29,040 --> 00:33:32,320
Yeah, great question.

535
00:33:32,320 --> 00:33:33,420
Cool.

536
00:33:33,420 --> 00:33:36,240
So we're still at the
candidate retrieval stage.

537
00:33:36,240 --> 00:33:43,320
And what we saw was one
way of retrieving documents

538
00:33:43,320 --> 00:33:45,160
from a similarity--

539
00:33:45,160 --> 00:33:48,100
sorry from a semantic
similarity standpoint.

540
00:33:48,100 --> 00:33:51,160
So by the way, what does
semantic similarity mean?

541
00:33:51,160 --> 00:33:57,250
It means is finding documents
or finding entities that

542
00:33:57,250 --> 00:34:01,250
have the same meaning
or that are relevant,

543
00:34:01,250 --> 00:34:04,450
but in the way that we
compute these embeddings,

544
00:34:04,450 --> 00:34:12,849
we're not enforcing any
kind of keyword match,

545
00:34:12,849 --> 00:34:16,090
like when we retrieve
documents in this way,

546
00:34:16,090 --> 00:34:19,929
it can very well be that the
documents that are matched,

547
00:34:19,929 --> 00:34:26,810
they do not have any word in
common, but they mean the same.

548
00:34:26,810 --> 00:34:30,730
Well, sometimes
you want to ensure

549
00:34:30,730 --> 00:34:33,510
that what you're looking for,
what you're searching for,

550
00:34:33,510 --> 00:34:38,730
is exactly containing the
keywords that is in your prompt.

551
00:34:38,730 --> 00:34:41,130
And in that case, you
would want to have

552
00:34:41,130 --> 00:34:44,610
a second way of doing things.

553
00:34:44,610 --> 00:34:48,530
So you may have
seen BM25 out there.

554
00:34:48,530 --> 00:34:56,429
So BM25 is a relevant score that
is actually a heuristic score.

555
00:34:56,429 --> 00:35:00,910
It is based on some
function of the overlap

556
00:35:00,910 --> 00:35:09,070
between what is in your query
and what is in your document.

557
00:35:09,070 --> 00:35:14,630
And so that one is actually
quite handy for cases, where

558
00:35:14,630 --> 00:35:18,270
you have a query
where you absolutely

559
00:35:18,270 --> 00:35:24,430
want to have documents that
contain keywords of this query.

560
00:35:24,430 --> 00:35:27,430
So here, I have an example that
I actually passed super briefly

561
00:35:27,430 --> 00:35:28,690
for the previous one.

562
00:35:28,690 --> 00:35:30,510
And we will come back to it.

563
00:35:30,510 --> 00:35:36,030
But let's suppose we have
let's say two teddy bears.

564
00:35:36,030 --> 00:35:40,910
One is named Cuddly and the
other one is named Huggy.

565
00:35:40,910 --> 00:35:44,590
So what you want is to
figure out where is Cuddly.

566
00:35:44,590 --> 00:35:47,830
So this is your query.

567
00:35:47,830 --> 00:35:51,770
So if you use BM25,
well, the answers

568
00:35:51,770 --> 00:35:56,810
that you are going to
get are by definition

569
00:35:56,810 --> 00:36:03,410
going to contain some overlap of
words that were in your query.

570
00:36:03,410 --> 00:36:06,650
And so here, you
will have, let's say

571
00:36:06,650 --> 00:36:10,290
documents that contain,
let's say where cuddly is.

572
00:36:10,290 --> 00:36:15,810
But if let's say you only
used these semantic similarity

573
00:36:15,810 --> 00:36:20,970
search, you would not
have that guarantee.

574
00:36:20,970 --> 00:36:27,330
You would only have documents
that are semantically similar.

575
00:36:27,330 --> 00:36:31,170
And those they
are not guaranteed

576
00:36:31,170 --> 00:36:33,850
to contain keywords
of your prompts.

577
00:36:33,850 --> 00:36:36,190
And so just to illustrate that.

578
00:36:36,190 --> 00:36:39,530
So here, Huggy and Cuddly,
they can be thought

579
00:36:39,530 --> 00:36:42,970
of semantically similar.

580
00:36:42,970 --> 00:36:45,610
So you will probably
not have cuddly--

581
00:36:45,610 --> 00:36:49,980
you will not necessarily
have cuddly in there.

582
00:36:49,980 --> 00:36:51,360
Just to illustrate that.

583
00:36:51,360 --> 00:36:56,260
And that is the reason
why nowadays, what people

584
00:36:56,260 --> 00:37:02,300
do is to look at the use cases
that they have and think about

585
00:37:02,300 --> 00:37:07,620
whether having some heuristic,
as well in the relevance score

586
00:37:07,620 --> 00:37:10,180
is useful for their use case.

587
00:37:10,180 --> 00:37:14,740
So some people, they go
with the hybrid combination

588
00:37:14,740 --> 00:37:19,780
of this embedding-based search
and the heuristic-based search.

589
00:37:19,780 --> 00:37:23,980
So some combination
of embeddings and BM25

590
00:37:23,980 --> 00:37:26,420
in which case you may have.

591
00:37:26,420 --> 00:37:29,200
Even more relevant documents,
depending on your use case.

592
00:37:32,660 --> 00:37:34,620
Does that make sense?

593
00:37:34,620 --> 00:37:36,220
Yeah.

594
00:37:36,220 --> 00:37:39,180
So now I'll come back to
what you mentioned about

595
00:37:39,180 --> 00:37:42,740
whether cutting
chunks in a naive way

596
00:37:42,740 --> 00:37:46,200
will necessarily lead you
to things that are coherent.

597
00:37:46,200 --> 00:37:47,700
Well, you're completely right.

598
00:37:47,700 --> 00:37:51,240
Sometimes you will not.

599
00:37:51,240 --> 00:37:53,700
But before we answer
this question,

600
00:37:53,700 --> 00:38:00,800
we actually are going to address
another concern, which is that

601
00:38:00,800 --> 00:38:06,960
typically, when people
want to ask about something

602
00:38:06,960 --> 00:38:11,160
in their LLM, the
query that they input

603
00:38:11,160 --> 00:38:15,160
is of a different
nature compared to what

604
00:38:15,160 --> 00:38:17,040
is in the knowledge base.

605
00:38:17,040 --> 00:38:20,200
So your query is typically
going to be maybe something

606
00:38:20,200 --> 00:38:22,880
short, maybe a question.

607
00:38:22,880 --> 00:38:26,260
But what is in your documents
is typically going to be longer.

608
00:38:26,260 --> 00:38:28,480
These are like
sentences and sentences.

609
00:38:28,480 --> 00:38:34,960
So if you really think about
it, if you use the same encoder

610
00:38:34,960 --> 00:38:40,120
to embed your query and
to embed your documents,

611
00:38:40,120 --> 00:38:45,050
well, these two embeddings,
they're not super comparable,

612
00:38:45,050 --> 00:38:47,370
because one is for a
question and the other one

613
00:38:47,370 --> 00:38:50,370
is for a document.

614
00:38:50,370 --> 00:38:54,970
So there's one extension that
tries to mitigate that issue.

615
00:38:54,970 --> 00:38:56,910
And I link the paper down there.

616
00:38:56,910 --> 00:38:59,690
So it's called the height.

617
00:38:59,690 --> 00:39:05,970
So what it does is instead
of computing the embedding

618
00:39:05,970 --> 00:39:13,290
related to the prompt, it will
first generate a fake document.

619
00:39:13,290 --> 00:39:18,970
So it's just an LLM call, a fake
document based on that prompt.

620
00:39:18,970 --> 00:39:23,170
And then embeds
that fake document

621
00:39:23,170 --> 00:39:24,400
to find relevant chunks.

622
00:39:27,010 --> 00:39:29,050
So it may or may not work.

623
00:39:29,050 --> 00:39:33,070
It's not used all
the time by everyone.

624
00:39:33,070 --> 00:39:34,930
So I would say
just something that

625
00:39:34,930 --> 00:39:37,030
is good to try to
see if that works.

626
00:39:37,030 --> 00:39:40,530
But this is one way
of mitigating this,

627
00:39:40,530 --> 00:39:44,150
another way could be
to simply have encoders

628
00:39:44,150 --> 00:39:49,590
that are specifically trained
to encode the query on one side

629
00:39:49,590 --> 00:39:53,250
and encode the documents
on the other side.

630
00:39:53,250 --> 00:39:56,790
In other words, to not
use the same encoder.

631
00:39:56,790 --> 00:39:58,870
People typically don't
do that, just because

632
00:39:58,870 --> 00:40:00,050
of maintenance purposes.

633
00:40:00,050 --> 00:40:01,717
But this could also
be another solution.

634
00:40:04,270 --> 00:40:07,350
So now, finally going
to your question

635
00:40:07,350 --> 00:40:11,230
regarding how we can make
sense of these chunks.

636
00:40:11,230 --> 00:40:12,730
If they are taken
out of context,

637
00:40:12,730 --> 00:40:14,630
they may not make sense.

638
00:40:14,630 --> 00:40:23,950
And so here, the idea here is to
prepend some piece of text that

639
00:40:23,950 --> 00:40:30,630
just sums up what you need to in
order to understand that chunk.

640
00:40:30,630 --> 00:40:34,350
So here, the idea is that
you have all your documents.

641
00:40:34,350 --> 00:40:37,550
Let's say you have one
document, that you divide it

642
00:40:37,550 --> 00:40:39,730
into n chunks.

643
00:40:39,730 --> 00:40:44,610
The idea here is instead
of considering these chunks

644
00:40:44,610 --> 00:40:51,530
separately, you're going to
compute some kind of context

645
00:40:51,530 --> 00:40:54,970
that is relevant to
each chunk, and that

646
00:40:54,970 --> 00:40:56,720
is based on the whole document.

647
00:40:59,570 --> 00:41:01,850
So how are you going to do that?

648
00:41:01,850 --> 00:41:03,970
Again, the LLM call.

649
00:41:03,970 --> 00:41:07,090
So what you do is
typically, have, let's say,

650
00:41:07,090 --> 00:41:08,230
the whole document.

651
00:41:08,230 --> 00:41:11,950
And then you have the chunk
that you want to contextualize.

652
00:41:11,950 --> 00:41:14,970
And you ask your model,
well, please give me

653
00:41:14,970 --> 00:41:21,090
a short succinct context to
just make sense of that chunk.

654
00:41:21,090 --> 00:41:25,090
And now you may tell me, well,
that's a lot of LLM calls.

655
00:41:25,090 --> 00:41:27,890
You have potentially
a lot of chunks.

656
00:41:27,890 --> 00:41:31,050
And that's just going
to be very pricey.

657
00:41:31,050 --> 00:41:37,540
Well, there's one strategy
to make this less expensive,

658
00:41:37,540 --> 00:41:40,920
and I'm not sure if
you've heard that option.

659
00:41:40,920 --> 00:41:44,340
It's called prompt caching.

660
00:41:44,340 --> 00:41:47,620
So now that you very
well how LLMs work,

661
00:41:47,620 --> 00:41:52,540
you know, typically, these
are decoder only and so on.

662
00:41:52,540 --> 00:42:02,340
So you know that if you
use the same prefix for all

663
00:42:02,340 --> 00:42:05,820
your prompts, well,
it's going to be

664
00:42:05,820 --> 00:42:08,620
the same computations that
you just do again and again

665
00:42:08,620 --> 00:42:10,380
and again.

666
00:42:10,380 --> 00:42:14,460
So the idea here is
you just do it once.

667
00:42:14,460 --> 00:42:18,740
And you save all the
relevant activations.

668
00:42:18,740 --> 00:42:21,320
And instead of
computing them again,

669
00:42:21,320 --> 00:42:25,060
you're just going to look
them up, just do a lookup,

670
00:42:25,060 --> 00:42:26,970
and then decode the rest.

671
00:42:30,020 --> 00:42:32,700
Does that make sense?

672
00:42:32,700 --> 00:42:35,340
Yeah.

673
00:42:35,340 --> 00:42:37,460
The question is activation
from a language model.

674
00:42:37,460 --> 00:42:41,440
Yes, because when you feed
a prompt to your model

675
00:42:41,440 --> 00:42:44,720
and you ask it to
generate a response,

676
00:42:44,720 --> 00:42:48,360
what the model needs to do is
well, to take all of this input

677
00:42:48,360 --> 00:42:51,700
and then compute the
activations of all the layers,

678
00:42:51,700 --> 00:42:54,760
and then have for the
generation process

679
00:42:54,760 --> 00:42:59,120
to have this attention across
all these other components.

680
00:42:59,120 --> 00:43:03,520
Well, given that it's
decoder only meaning,

681
00:43:03,520 --> 00:43:07,120
it's only left to right.

682
00:43:07,120 --> 00:43:10,280
The thing that you
input, if it's the same,

683
00:43:10,280 --> 00:43:14,340
then it will lead to
the same activations.

684
00:43:14,340 --> 00:43:14,840
Yeah.

685
00:43:20,640 --> 00:43:22,800
The question is, what if
you have a closed model

686
00:43:22,800 --> 00:43:25,120
where prompt caching,
and I'm going

687
00:43:25,120 --> 00:43:28,240
to just talk about
this in just one slide,

688
00:43:28,240 --> 00:43:35,940
is an option that is closed
models or providers offer?

689
00:43:35,940 --> 00:43:39,380
And what they tell
you is, well, this

690
00:43:39,380 --> 00:43:42,660
is the same prefix
for all your prompts.

691
00:43:42,660 --> 00:43:44,820
So what we're going to
do is we're just going

692
00:43:44,820 --> 00:43:47,900
to make it cheaper for you.

693
00:43:47,900 --> 00:43:52,020
So if you look at the
model pricing page,

694
00:43:52,020 --> 00:43:56,820
you will see that there is
a price for regular inputs.

695
00:43:56,820 --> 00:43:59,740
So inputs that are not cached.

696
00:43:59,740 --> 00:44:04,540
And then you have the price
per cached input token.

697
00:44:04,540 --> 00:44:07,460
And here, you see for the
let's say, OpenAI model,

698
00:44:07,460 --> 00:44:11,540
it's 110th of the price.

699
00:44:11,540 --> 00:44:14,460
So I guess, what do I
want to tell you by this?

700
00:44:14,460 --> 00:44:17,860
Well, just try to be
smart with the prompts

701
00:44:17,860 --> 00:44:21,340
and try to gather
all the things that

702
00:44:21,340 --> 00:44:25,380
are likely to be repeated
across prompts in the beginning.

703
00:44:25,380 --> 00:44:32,670
So that you can leverage
this nice percentage off.

704
00:44:32,670 --> 00:44:35,190
Does that make sense?

705
00:44:35,190 --> 00:44:35,690
OK.

706
00:44:35,690 --> 00:44:38,150
Cool.

707
00:44:38,150 --> 00:44:38,790
Great.

708
00:44:38,790 --> 00:44:43,150
So up until now,
we have seen how

709
00:44:43,150 --> 00:44:46,830
we can go from potentially
thousands or even, let's say,

710
00:44:46,830 --> 00:44:52,110
millions of chunks up to,
or down to, let's say,

711
00:44:52,110 --> 00:44:55,670
hundreds of potentially
relevant chunks.

712
00:44:55,670 --> 00:44:59,070
Now, what we want to
do is to sort them

713
00:44:59,070 --> 00:45:01,270
in a more meaningful way.

714
00:45:01,270 --> 00:45:03,450
And the second part
is more optional,

715
00:45:03,450 --> 00:45:08,150
because maybe sometimes this
first cut that we've done

716
00:45:08,150 --> 00:45:12,550
may be good enough, but I
guess this second step is

717
00:45:12,550 --> 00:45:15,150
about being more
intentional in how

718
00:45:15,150 --> 00:45:21,610
we give the final score to be
able to really select the final,

719
00:45:21,610 --> 00:45:24,310
let's say, top k chunks.

720
00:45:24,310 --> 00:45:30,450
So the second stage is called
ranking or even re-ranking.

721
00:45:30,450 --> 00:45:33,450
Re-ranking because, I
guess, with the first step,

722
00:45:33,450 --> 00:45:35,410
you already have some ranking.

723
00:45:35,410 --> 00:45:37,610
So we're re-ranking.

724
00:45:37,610 --> 00:45:41,250
And what we're doing
is instead of using

725
00:45:41,250 --> 00:45:44,290
this very quick
operation, similarity

726
00:45:44,290 --> 00:45:48,770
operation between embeddings
that we've computed,

727
00:45:48,770 --> 00:45:50,570
we're going to use
something that is maybe

728
00:45:50,570 --> 00:45:53,250
a bit more sophisticated.

729
00:45:53,250 --> 00:45:57,730
So instead of considering
the query and the chunk

730
00:45:57,730 --> 00:46:01,330
separately, what
we're going to do

731
00:46:01,330 --> 00:46:08,010
is to actually put them both
in the encoder, both of them,

732
00:46:08,010 --> 00:46:11,210
and have a relevance
score out of that.

733
00:46:11,210 --> 00:46:15,170
So the reason why it may be a
little bit more meaningful to do

734
00:46:15,170 --> 00:46:18,850
it this way is that
you have a model that

735
00:46:18,850 --> 00:46:24,130
takes a look at both your query
and your chunk at the same time

736
00:46:24,130 --> 00:46:27,390
and gives you a score.

737
00:46:27,390 --> 00:46:30,750
Whereas in the first step,
you had one embedding

738
00:46:30,750 --> 00:46:34,430
for the query and one
embedding for the chunk,

739
00:46:34,430 --> 00:46:37,910
which didn't have that
interaction that a model could

740
00:46:37,910 --> 00:46:40,110
capture.

741
00:46:40,110 --> 00:46:43,510
And you will also see
out there that this setup

742
00:46:43,510 --> 00:46:47,910
is called cross-encoder
setup because you

743
00:46:47,910 --> 00:46:52,890
have both your inputs
fed to your encoder.

744
00:46:52,890 --> 00:46:55,910
So there's some
cross interactions.

745
00:46:55,910 --> 00:47:00,370
So if you remember the first
approach is a bi-encoder setup.

746
00:47:00,370 --> 00:47:02,200
And this one is a cross-encoder.

747
00:47:09,490 --> 00:47:09,990
Yeah.

748
00:47:09,990 --> 00:47:11,740
The question is, you
will actually compute

749
00:47:11,740 --> 00:47:13,530
the attention between the two.

750
00:47:13,530 --> 00:47:17,230
Yes, absolutely.

751
00:47:17,230 --> 00:47:22,810
And here, sentence there they
have a lot of good documents.

752
00:47:22,810 --> 00:47:24,730
So I highly recommend
just reading their docs.

753
00:47:24,730 --> 00:47:28,280
They're at the
bottom of the slide.

754
00:47:28,280 --> 00:47:29,400
Cool.

755
00:47:29,400 --> 00:47:35,000
Well, you do that on all your
potentially relevant chunks.

756
00:47:35,000 --> 00:47:38,000
So you have this
score that is computed

757
00:47:38,000 --> 00:47:42,040
for each of these
chunks with the prompts.

758
00:47:42,040 --> 00:47:46,840
And then you finally
obtain the ranking.

759
00:47:46,840 --> 00:47:51,720
And now the question is, are
you happy with the ranking?

760
00:47:51,720 --> 00:47:53,620
And in order to
answer that question,

761
00:47:53,620 --> 00:47:58,400
you need a way to
quantify your performance.

762
00:47:58,400 --> 00:48:02,760
And that's where we're going to
see in the next five minutes.

763
00:48:02,760 --> 00:48:06,360
What are the metrics that
we typically use to do that?

764
00:48:06,360 --> 00:48:09,240
So again, this is
very similar to if you

765
00:48:09,240 --> 00:48:11,140
do search or recommendation.

766
00:48:11,140 --> 00:48:14,560
So in case you have
a background there,

767
00:48:14,560 --> 00:48:18,000
you will see some commonalities.

768
00:48:18,000 --> 00:48:20,680
So here's the setup.

769
00:48:20,680 --> 00:48:23,360
You have a bunch of chunks.

770
00:48:23,360 --> 00:48:27,100
You do this first
and second step.

771
00:48:27,100 --> 00:48:28,940
And at the end of
the day, you will

772
00:48:28,940 --> 00:48:32,480
have k chunks that
will come at the top,

773
00:48:32,480 --> 00:48:37,220
that you will qualify
as being relevant.

774
00:48:37,220 --> 00:48:40,460
And you want to compare
that with respect

775
00:48:40,460 --> 00:48:44,060
to actually relevant chunks.

776
00:48:44,060 --> 00:48:48,380
So you can think of it as
you have label like, same as

777
00:48:48,380 --> 00:48:49,920
in binary classification.

778
00:48:49,920 --> 00:48:52,480
So you have relevant
and not relevant,

779
00:48:52,480 --> 00:48:54,180
and you predict some
that are relevant

780
00:48:54,180 --> 00:48:58,180
and you want to know
well you're doing.

781
00:48:58,180 --> 00:49:00,540
So this is the setup.

782
00:49:00,540 --> 00:49:04,420
Well, when it comes
to ranking, you

783
00:49:04,420 --> 00:49:08,700
need to somehow incorporate
this information

784
00:49:08,700 --> 00:49:12,820
of how high in the
ranking you've put stuff.

785
00:49:12,820 --> 00:49:14,820
So here, let's
suppose that you have

786
00:49:14,820 --> 00:49:21,240
ranked this n chunks from most
important to least important.

787
00:49:21,240 --> 00:49:24,870
So let's suppose you have
first, second, third, and so on,

788
00:49:24,870 --> 00:49:27,390
and so forth.

789
00:49:27,390 --> 00:49:31,430
And you only care
about the first k,

790
00:49:31,430 --> 00:49:34,070
because in the rack
setting, you typically

791
00:49:34,070 --> 00:49:37,030
retrieve the top k
that are relevant.

792
00:49:37,030 --> 00:49:41,670
And you put all these
top k in your prompt.

793
00:49:41,670 --> 00:49:47,230
Well, the first metric that you
will likely use is called NDCG.

794
00:49:49,990 --> 00:49:51,090
It's a lot of letters.

795
00:49:51,090 --> 00:49:53,550
I'm going to just
explain what that means.

796
00:49:53,550 --> 00:50:01,310
So NDCG tries to quantify
how good your ranking is

797
00:50:01,310 --> 00:50:04,470
by taking into
consideration where

798
00:50:04,470 --> 00:50:08,830
you ranked relevant documents.

799
00:50:08,830 --> 00:50:12,230
So you have this formula
that may seem scary,

800
00:50:12,230 --> 00:50:16,290
but it's actually quite
simple what it's trying to do.

801
00:50:16,290 --> 00:50:23,170
So it's trying to incentivize
the score to be higher.

802
00:50:23,170 --> 00:50:27,850
If your ranking the
relevant documents

803
00:50:27,850 --> 00:50:31,050
closer to the first position.

804
00:50:31,050 --> 00:50:38,130
So what it does, is it is the
sum over the first k positions

805
00:50:38,130 --> 00:50:39,970
that you're ranked.

806
00:50:39,970 --> 00:50:42,170
And it is looking
at whether what

807
00:50:42,170 --> 00:50:47,410
you've ranked for each of these
positions is relevant or not.

808
00:50:47,410 --> 00:50:50,730
So for instance, it
checks the first position.

809
00:50:50,730 --> 00:50:52,350
First position is
irrelevant or not.

810
00:50:52,350 --> 00:50:55,450
So relevance-- if it's
relevant, it's one.

811
00:50:55,450 --> 00:51:01,450
So it's one over some quantity
that is a function of the rank.

812
00:51:01,450 --> 00:51:05,170
And it does that
for all the ranks.

813
00:51:05,170 --> 00:51:09,450
So the score will
be higher if you

814
00:51:09,450 --> 00:51:13,490
rank relevant documents high.

815
00:51:13,490 --> 00:51:16,890
So that's basically the
goal of this metric.

816
00:51:16,890 --> 00:51:21,630
So this part is the
discounted cumulative gain.

817
00:51:21,630 --> 00:51:23,630
So it's cumulative
gain because you're

818
00:51:23,630 --> 00:51:28,470
looking at basically, if
you had relevant documents

819
00:51:28,470 --> 00:51:33,430
in your first k positions,
which is cumulative part,

820
00:51:33,430 --> 00:51:36,910
it's discounted because
it's better for you

821
00:51:36,910 --> 00:51:40,970
to have a relevant
document in position one,

822
00:51:40,970 --> 00:51:42,990
let's say, than position k.

823
00:51:42,990 --> 00:51:48,150
And you can see that
in the denominator.

824
00:51:48,150 --> 00:51:50,610
Now, why do we say NDCG?

825
00:51:50,610 --> 00:51:53,230
What is the normalization part?

826
00:51:53,230 --> 00:51:57,710
Well, this metric can take
a lot of different values,

827
00:51:57,710 --> 00:52:00,790
depending on how many
relevant documents there are.

828
00:52:00,790 --> 00:52:06,370
So what people do is they
compute the quote, unquote,

829
00:52:06,370 --> 00:52:10,390
"ideal or optimal
or upper bound"

830
00:52:10,390 --> 00:52:13,670
DCG that you can get
for a given query,

831
00:52:13,670 --> 00:52:19,960
and they call that ideal DCG,
and they just normalized DCG

832
00:52:19,960 --> 00:52:20,560
over IDCG.

833
00:52:23,320 --> 00:52:27,360
So the reason why
they do that is they

834
00:52:27,360 --> 00:52:29,920
want you to score
a score of one,

835
00:52:29,920 --> 00:52:34,120
if you are matching
the optimal ranking.

836
00:52:34,120 --> 00:52:37,060
They basically want to
make the score meaningful.

837
00:52:39,600 --> 00:52:42,460
So does this make sense?

838
00:52:42,460 --> 00:52:42,960
Yeah?

839
00:52:52,440 --> 00:52:55,940
So the question is, how do they
compute the relevance score?

840
00:52:55,940 --> 00:52:59,160
So you can think
step one and step two

841
00:52:59,160 --> 00:53:03,280
as being a two-step
process for you

842
00:53:03,280 --> 00:53:08,040
to say which documents you
are saying are relevant.

843
00:53:08,040 --> 00:53:11,440
So at the end of
this two-step stage,

844
00:53:11,440 --> 00:53:16,340
the ones that you say
are relevant are here.

845
00:53:16,340 --> 00:53:20,900
Now, you typically have a
score for each retrieved chunk.

846
00:53:20,900 --> 00:53:25,220
So you're going to
sort these chunks.

847
00:53:25,220 --> 00:53:30,580
You're going to sort them by
the score in a descending order.

848
00:53:30,580 --> 00:53:33,100
And the relevance here
that you're going to use

849
00:53:33,100 --> 00:53:34,400
is the actual label.

850
00:53:34,400 --> 00:53:39,300
So is the chunk actually
relevant or not?

851
00:53:39,300 --> 00:53:44,340
So you're going to look at
your k retrieved chunks,

852
00:53:44,340 --> 00:53:46,400
and you're going to
ask yourself, OK,

853
00:53:46,400 --> 00:53:48,597
is the first chunk
actually relevant?

854
00:53:48,597 --> 00:53:49,430
So you have a label.

855
00:53:49,430 --> 00:53:52,620
You know which ones are
relevant, which ones are not.

856
00:53:52,620 --> 00:53:54,803
And these ones are
going to be the ones

857
00:53:54,803 --> 00:53:55,970
you will use in the formula.

858
00:53:58,540 --> 00:53:59,840
Yes, that's the ground truth.

859
00:53:59,840 --> 00:54:00,380
Exactly.

860
00:54:00,380 --> 00:54:00,880
Yeah.

861
00:54:04,600 --> 00:54:05,100
Cool.

862
00:54:05,100 --> 00:54:07,500
Does that make sense?

863
00:54:07,500 --> 00:54:08,980
Yeah.

864
00:54:08,980 --> 00:54:09,480
OK.

865
00:54:09,480 --> 00:54:10,660
Great.

866
00:54:10,660 --> 00:54:12,540
So you have a bunch
of other metrics.

867
00:54:12,540 --> 00:54:16,280
You have another one that's
called the reciprocal rank.

868
00:54:16,280 --> 00:54:19,440
So this one is much simpler.

869
00:54:19,440 --> 00:54:27,120
It takes the inverse
of the highest rank

870
00:54:27,120 --> 00:54:29,980
of all the relevant documents.

871
00:54:29,980 --> 00:54:34,720
So if let's suppose in
your top k documents,

872
00:54:34,720 --> 00:54:38,040
let's suppose the first
relevant document, let's say,

873
00:54:38,040 --> 00:54:40,320
comes at rank number two.

874
00:54:40,320 --> 00:54:43,200
Then rank will be equal to two.

875
00:54:43,200 --> 00:54:47,800
So it basically does not care
about any relevant documents

876
00:54:47,800 --> 00:54:51,800
that are past that
first relevant document.

877
00:54:51,800 --> 00:54:54,000
So this is just like
a simpler metric

878
00:54:54,000 --> 00:54:56,440
that typically correlates well.

879
00:54:56,440 --> 00:54:59,280
So that's why people use it.

880
00:54:59,280 --> 00:55:01,160
And then, of course,
you're familiar

881
00:55:01,160 --> 00:55:04,320
with the classic
classification metrics--

882
00:55:04,320 --> 00:55:06,440
recall and precision.

883
00:55:06,440 --> 00:55:09,480
So if you remember, if
you have two classes,

884
00:55:09,480 --> 00:55:14,290
you have the positive class,
you have the negative class.

885
00:55:14,290 --> 00:55:18,330
So recall, what it
does is it takes

886
00:55:18,330 --> 00:55:24,290
a look at all the actually
positive observations,

887
00:55:24,290 --> 00:55:28,650
and it tries to ask itself among
all these actually positive

888
00:55:28,650 --> 00:55:34,370
samples, which are the ones that
you actually predicted positive?

889
00:55:34,370 --> 00:55:36,570
That's the recall
that you all know.

890
00:55:36,570 --> 00:55:40,770
And there is, I guess, a
ranking equivalent, which

891
00:55:40,770 --> 00:55:44,950
is out of all the documents
that are relevant,

892
00:55:44,950 --> 00:55:49,850
actually relevant, so this is
like your positive class, which

893
00:55:49,850 --> 00:55:55,330
are the ones that you actually
predicted as being relevant?

894
00:55:55,330 --> 00:56:01,450
So this is basically which
ones are in the top k?

895
00:56:01,450 --> 00:56:04,790
And similarly, you also have
the precision equivalent.

896
00:56:04,790 --> 00:56:09,390
So if you remember, precision
is out of all the ones

897
00:56:09,390 --> 00:56:14,230
that you have predicted to be
positives, how many of them

898
00:56:14,230 --> 00:56:17,590
are actually positive?

899
00:56:17,590 --> 00:56:19,170
So this is the equivalent here.

900
00:56:19,170 --> 00:56:21,730
So which are the ones that
you've predicted to be positive?

901
00:56:21,730 --> 00:56:26,950
So which are the ones that you
have selected in your top k?

902
00:56:26,950 --> 00:56:30,250
And among those ones, which
ones are actually positive?

903
00:56:30,250 --> 00:56:31,860
So which ones are
actually relevant?

904
00:56:35,590 --> 00:56:38,310
Does that make sense?

905
00:56:38,310 --> 00:56:40,910
So I guess these four metrics--

906
00:56:40,910 --> 00:56:44,910
NDCG, MRR, precision
at k, recall at k,

907
00:56:44,910 --> 00:56:47,510
we see this in a
bunch of papers.

908
00:56:47,510 --> 00:56:49,230
So I just highly
recommend you just

909
00:56:49,230 --> 00:56:53,070
get familiar with their ideas
and maybe with the formula.

910
00:56:53,070 --> 00:56:57,070
And these would be the ones
that you would use to quantify,

911
00:56:57,070 --> 00:57:00,950
whether your retriever is
doing a good job or not.

912
00:57:00,950 --> 00:57:03,410
So you have a bunch of
benchmarks out there.

913
00:57:03,410 --> 00:57:05,730
So there is one that is
actually quite popular.

914
00:57:05,730 --> 00:57:10,570
It's is called massive
text embedding benchmark.

915
00:57:10,570 --> 00:57:12,470
So if you want to
test your retriever,

916
00:57:12,470 --> 00:57:17,690
if it performs well or not would
typically take it, and then

917
00:57:17,690 --> 00:57:20,170
just evaluate it
on that benchmark,

918
00:57:20,170 --> 00:57:22,790
and then have all
these metrics computed.

919
00:57:22,790 --> 00:57:24,850
And then if you have
different solutions,

920
00:57:24,850 --> 00:57:26,860
you would typically
compare this metric.

921
00:57:29,850 --> 00:57:33,330
And with that, we,
I guess, hopefully,

922
00:57:33,330 --> 00:57:37,130
have a better sense of
how to build a RAG system

923
00:57:37,130 --> 00:57:41,690
and specifically how to
have a good retriever.

924
00:57:41,690 --> 00:57:44,570
So we have just maybe
one more minute.

925
00:57:44,570 --> 00:57:48,430
Is there any questions
on that first part?

926
00:57:48,430 --> 00:57:48,930
Yeah?

927
00:57:58,490 --> 00:58:00,450
So the question is,
so for the re-ranking,

928
00:58:00,450 --> 00:58:03,190
we're using an encoder that
will output a relevance score.

929
00:58:03,190 --> 00:58:07,100
So we will typically train
a model that does that.

930
00:58:07,100 --> 00:58:08,700
So there are typically--

931
00:58:08,700 --> 00:58:10,760
I believe there are
some pre-trained ones,

932
00:58:10,760 --> 00:58:16,440
but out there, you can very
well have your custom one.

933
00:58:16,440 --> 00:58:20,100
So that model will typically
be a bit more sophisticated

934
00:58:20,100 --> 00:58:22,020
compared to the first step.

935
00:58:22,020 --> 00:58:24,980
Because here, you can
afford to spend more time

936
00:58:24,980 --> 00:58:28,340
to produce that score because
you're operating out of,

937
00:58:28,340 --> 00:58:31,520
let's say, over 100
possible candidates,

938
00:58:31,520 --> 00:58:35,180
as opposed to let's
say, much more millions

939
00:58:35,180 --> 00:58:38,040
or hundreds of thousands.

940
00:58:38,040 --> 00:58:41,200
So that's the idea.

941
00:58:41,200 --> 00:58:41,700
Yeah?

942
00:58:46,820 --> 00:58:50,500
So the question is, how about
training with contrastive loss?

943
00:58:50,500 --> 00:58:54,420
This is a detail, we
not I guess, cover here.

944
00:58:54,420 --> 00:58:56,660
But in order to
train these models,

945
00:58:56,660 --> 00:59:00,540
you'll have a bunch of different
types of loss function.

946
00:59:00,540 --> 00:59:05,080
So I highly recommend you
read the S-BERT paper,

947
00:59:05,080 --> 00:59:07,800
because in that paper, there
are several loss functions

948
00:59:07,800 --> 00:59:10,160
that the paper tries to compare.

949
00:59:10,160 --> 00:59:12,215
And this is one of them.

950
00:59:12,215 --> 00:59:13,340
So that's a great question.

951
00:59:13,340 --> 00:59:17,760
I highly recommend reading
the S-BERT paper for that.

952
00:59:17,760 --> 00:59:19,080
Cool.

953
00:59:19,080 --> 00:59:21,520
With that, I'll
give it to Shervine.

954
00:59:21,520 --> 00:59:24,040
Thank you, Afshine.

955
00:59:24,040 --> 00:59:28,220
So thanks a lot for covering
the RAG methodology.

956
00:59:28,220 --> 00:59:32,560
So now, we arrive at my
favorite part of the lecture.

957
00:59:32,560 --> 00:59:35,980
We're going to see tool
calling and the agentic world.

958
00:59:35,980 --> 00:59:38,960
And we're going to see
how much more powerful

959
00:59:38,960 --> 00:59:42,680
your LLMs are going to
become just in a second.

960
00:59:42,680 --> 00:59:45,240
So what Afshine
just mentioned is

961
00:59:45,240 --> 00:59:48,000
how you would deal
with incorporating

962
00:59:48,000 --> 00:59:53,280
data that is not structured as
part of your prompts to the LLM.

963
00:59:53,280 --> 00:59:57,120
And now, we're going to
see what we could do more.

964
00:59:57,120 --> 01:00:01,300
In the case, the data that we
want to inject is structured.

965
01:00:01,300 --> 01:00:04,100
So in the case of RAG,
you have documents

966
01:00:04,100 --> 01:00:05,700
with words and words and words.

967
01:00:05,700 --> 01:00:09,260
And you just want to fetch
the relevant documents

968
01:00:09,260 --> 01:00:10,980
to answer your prompts.

969
01:00:10,980 --> 01:00:13,780
But here, let's
suppose that you have

970
01:00:13,780 --> 01:00:20,900
some structure that determines
input/outputs in your data.

971
01:00:20,900 --> 01:00:23,760
So typically, you could
represent it maybe as a table.

972
01:00:23,760 --> 01:00:25,880
So you have separate columns.

973
01:00:25,880 --> 01:00:28,980
And then depending on the
value of given columns,

974
01:00:28,980 --> 01:00:31,380
you have a given output.

975
01:00:31,380 --> 01:00:36,180
So we could probably
reframe that setup

976
01:00:36,180 --> 01:00:39,120
into a function, a setup.

977
01:00:39,120 --> 01:00:41,920
So we mentioned tool calling.

978
01:00:41,920 --> 01:00:45,780
And then this rephrasing is
called the function calling.

979
01:00:45,780 --> 01:00:50,740
So let's suppose that you get
this relationship between input

980
01:00:50,740 --> 01:00:55,700
and output through a function
for the rest of this part.

981
01:00:55,700 --> 01:00:58,630
And then here, if
I had to transpose

982
01:00:58,630 --> 01:01:03,950
what the result of a given ID
and field and other arguments

983
01:01:03,950 --> 01:01:06,150
would look like, you
could interpret it

984
01:01:06,150 --> 01:01:09,830
as a function with
these as arguments.

985
01:01:09,830 --> 01:01:13,033
And the output would be simply
what you have as an output

986
01:01:13,033 --> 01:01:13,700
to the function.

987
01:01:16,590 --> 01:01:19,350
In the world of tool
calling and function

988
01:01:19,350 --> 01:01:21,750
calling, very
oftentimes, you're going

989
01:01:21,750 --> 01:01:26,390
to see that LLMs tend to
use Python as a language,

990
01:01:26,390 --> 01:01:29,590
just because it's
so simple to read.

991
01:01:29,590 --> 01:01:32,790
So this is what we are going
to use as an example as well.

992
01:01:32,790 --> 01:01:36,610
But there is nothing that
ties us to Python necessarily.

993
01:01:36,610 --> 01:01:39,970
So you could well have a tool
calling in other languages.

994
01:01:42,510 --> 01:01:44,590
Just as a note.

995
01:01:44,590 --> 01:01:47,890
Any questions on the setup?

996
01:01:47,890 --> 01:01:48,390
OK.

997
01:01:48,390 --> 01:01:50,750
Awesome.

998
01:01:50,750 --> 01:01:53,590
So there is nothing
controversial about tool

999
01:01:53,590 --> 01:01:57,410
calling, but I'm going to
still state a full definition

1000
01:01:57,410 --> 01:02:00,210
to make sure that we
are on the same page.

1001
01:02:00,210 --> 01:02:02,730
So I was browsing
here and there,

1002
01:02:02,730 --> 01:02:05,370
and I tried to find an
authoritative source.

1003
01:02:05,370 --> 01:02:08,290
And this website
like on IBM, there

1004
01:02:08,290 --> 01:02:10,770
is an article that defines--

1005
01:02:10,770 --> 01:02:12,670
that tries to define
what tool calling is.

1006
01:02:12,670 --> 01:02:17,330
So I'm going to anchor on
their definition from now on.

1007
01:02:17,330 --> 01:02:19,490
So I'm going to read out loud.

1008
01:02:19,490 --> 01:02:21,850
So tool calling allows
autonomous systems

1009
01:02:21,850 --> 01:02:26,810
to complete complex tasks
by dynamically accessing

1010
01:02:26,810 --> 01:02:30,610
and may act upon
external resources.

1011
01:02:30,610 --> 01:02:35,170
So the things that I want you
to get from that are two things.

1012
01:02:35,170 --> 01:02:39,670
So first, you have the notion
of completing some task.

1013
01:02:39,670 --> 01:02:44,890
So given an input and you have
to complete some task and then

1014
01:02:44,890 --> 01:02:49,810
the reliance potentially
on external resources.

1015
01:02:49,810 --> 01:02:51,550
So it doesn't have
to be external.

1016
01:02:51,550 --> 01:02:53,990
You don't have to rely
on external resources.

1017
01:02:53,990 --> 01:02:57,420
But this is one
potential property

1018
01:02:57,420 --> 01:03:02,340
that can help you fill the gap
that Afshine was mentioning

1019
01:03:02,340 --> 01:03:06,860
at the beginning of the lecture,
regarding filling the knowledge

1020
01:03:06,860 --> 01:03:10,460
gap that your
pre-trained LLM has.

1021
01:03:10,460 --> 01:03:14,500
So we're going to see
examples in a few minutes,

1022
01:03:14,500 --> 01:03:16,660
regarding what that could mean.

1023
01:03:16,660 --> 01:03:22,620
But yeah, this is one
magical part of it.

1024
01:03:22,620 --> 01:03:23,120
OK.

1025
01:03:23,120 --> 01:03:24,940
Great.

1026
01:03:24,940 --> 01:03:30,340
And just to make
these statements very

1027
01:03:30,340 --> 01:03:33,420
grounded in real-life
applications,

1028
01:03:33,420 --> 01:03:38,100
let's just walk through what
would a tool call give us

1029
01:03:38,100 --> 01:03:40,860
in the case of a very
specific example?

1030
01:03:40,860 --> 01:03:44,780
So let's suppose you
love teddy bears.

1031
01:03:44,780 --> 01:03:47,140
You're currently
here at Stanford,

1032
01:03:47,140 --> 01:03:49,340
and you want a
teddy bear near you.

1033
01:03:49,340 --> 01:03:52,640
What if you pull your
phone out, and you just

1034
01:03:52,640 --> 01:03:55,480
ask, find a teddy bear near me.

1035
01:03:55,480 --> 01:03:59,240
Well, your current
LLM, without any tools,

1036
01:03:59,240 --> 01:04:03,040
would not know some
real-life or like

1037
01:04:03,040 --> 01:04:09,720
real-time update of availability
of teddy bears near you.

1038
01:04:09,720 --> 01:04:13,080
So it would probably answer
you something in the flavor of,

1039
01:04:13,080 --> 01:04:16,320
I don't know or not sure.

1040
01:04:16,320 --> 01:04:20,720
And I just want to say
that with the use of tools,

1041
01:04:20,720 --> 01:04:23,600
let's see how we
could get to a stage

1042
01:04:23,600 --> 01:04:26,200
where we can inject
the information that

1043
01:04:26,200 --> 01:04:31,360
is necessary for the LLM to know
how to respond to your query.

1044
01:04:31,360 --> 01:04:34,040
And the goal of the
next few minutes

1045
01:04:34,040 --> 01:04:37,200
is going to be for
us to figure out,

1046
01:04:37,200 --> 01:04:41,400
both what we could do
what-- what we could inject

1047
01:04:41,400 --> 01:04:44,040
in the preamble of the LLM?

1048
01:04:44,040 --> 01:04:48,400
And what would be the steps that
we could go through in order

1049
01:04:48,400 --> 01:04:49,650
to complete such a request?

1050
01:04:52,420 --> 01:04:56,080
Does that make sense so far?

1051
01:04:56,080 --> 01:04:56,580
Yeah?

1052
01:05:02,700 --> 01:05:06,080
So the question is, are those
function APIs pre-computed?

1053
01:05:06,080 --> 01:05:07,320
So that's a great question.

1054
01:05:07,320 --> 01:05:09,720
So yes, you define
them beforehand.

1055
01:05:09,720 --> 01:05:11,420
You have some API.

1056
01:05:11,420 --> 01:05:13,360
And we're going to
see that in a second.

1057
01:05:13,360 --> 01:05:15,560
They're not LLM
generated on the fly.

1058
01:05:19,640 --> 01:05:20,140
OK.

1059
01:05:20,140 --> 01:05:20,640
Great.

1060
01:05:20,640 --> 01:05:23,620
Any other questions
on the setup?

1061
01:05:23,620 --> 01:05:25,880
So I know it will
be a lot to take in.

1062
01:05:28,720 --> 01:05:29,220
OK.

1063
01:05:29,220 --> 01:05:30,300
Great.

1064
01:05:30,300 --> 01:05:34,320
So in order to be
grounded in real life,

1065
01:05:34,320 --> 01:05:38,260
let's take a full example of
what a function definition could

1066
01:05:38,260 --> 01:05:39,100
be.

1067
01:05:39,100 --> 01:05:42,220
So in the case of
finding a teddy bear,

1068
01:05:42,220 --> 01:05:45,340
you could imagine a
function definition

1069
01:05:45,340 --> 01:05:48,580
that is called find teddy bear.

1070
01:05:48,580 --> 01:05:54,310
And depending on your
location, calls some API

1071
01:05:54,310 --> 01:05:58,790
and retrieves
potential candidates.

1072
01:05:58,790 --> 01:06:03,950
So I'm going to go through the
main characteristics of what

1073
01:06:03,950 --> 01:06:09,530
a function call contains and
link it to the definition.

1074
01:06:09,530 --> 01:06:13,310
So first of all, when we
want to display such an API

1075
01:06:13,310 --> 01:06:15,950
to the model, you
need to document

1076
01:06:15,950 --> 01:06:18,870
it, its input and
output, in order

1077
01:06:18,870 --> 01:06:22,510
for the model to what
this function is for.

1078
01:06:22,510 --> 01:06:25,310
So typically, the
description that you

1079
01:06:25,310 --> 01:06:29,030
have in the example of
Python under a given function

1080
01:06:29,030 --> 01:06:34,070
would be crucial for the model
to know what it is about.

1081
01:06:34,070 --> 01:06:39,482
And then we saw in the
definition of tool call

1082
01:06:39,482 --> 01:06:41,710
that we just gave, that
we have the ability

1083
01:06:41,710 --> 01:06:43,710
to make backend calls.

1084
01:06:43,710 --> 01:06:45,830
And this is exactly
what we would

1085
01:06:45,830 --> 01:06:50,210
need to do in the case of
finding teddy bears around you.

1086
01:06:50,210 --> 01:06:53,290
You would need to query
some API to retrieve

1087
01:06:53,290 --> 01:06:54,750
available teddy bears.

1088
01:06:54,750 --> 01:06:59,290
And based on your location,
return the nearest ones.

1089
01:06:59,290 --> 01:07:03,380
So this is exactly what
this function implementation

1090
01:07:03,380 --> 01:07:03,880
is doing.

1091
01:07:08,610 --> 01:07:11,810
It returns something
that is well structured.

1092
01:07:11,810 --> 01:07:15,110
So you see maybe it's
small from where you are,

1093
01:07:15,110 --> 01:07:19,290
but you have some
class definition that

1094
01:07:19,290 --> 01:07:21,610
puts some structure
into the output

1095
01:07:21,610 --> 01:07:24,290
and makes it interpretable.

1096
01:07:24,290 --> 01:07:27,530
And we're going to see very
soon that this output is going

1097
01:07:27,530 --> 01:07:31,250
to be what the model
will anchor on in order

1098
01:07:31,250 --> 01:07:32,820
to give its final response.

1099
01:07:36,370 --> 01:07:36,870
OK.

1100
01:07:36,870 --> 01:07:38,130
Great.

1101
01:07:38,130 --> 01:07:42,890
And one other thing I
will say is all of these

1102
01:07:42,890 --> 01:07:47,110
that we see here is what
you have implemented.

1103
01:07:47,110 --> 01:07:49,790
You will not see all of these--

1104
01:07:49,790 --> 01:07:52,390
if you are an LLM, you
will not see all of this.

1105
01:07:52,390 --> 01:07:58,430
All you care about as an LLM
is the function API, the input

1106
01:07:58,430 --> 01:08:02,590
and output, as well as the
main lines of documentations.

1107
01:08:02,590 --> 01:08:05,050
So all these
implementation details,

1108
01:08:05,050 --> 01:08:07,970
you're going to have
it on your code base.

1109
01:08:07,970 --> 01:08:11,850
But the LLM is not
going to see it.

1110
01:08:11,850 --> 01:08:12,350
OK.

1111
01:08:12,350 --> 01:08:13,670
Great.

1112
01:08:13,670 --> 01:08:17,710
So now, let's go
step-by-step into how

1113
01:08:17,710 --> 01:08:20,670
we could make this work.

1114
01:08:20,670 --> 01:08:26,149
So the first stage is as
you ask a question that

1115
01:08:26,149 --> 01:08:29,270
is related to your
function, you would

1116
01:08:29,270 --> 01:08:34,430
insert at the beginning of
your preamble the function API.

1117
01:08:34,430 --> 01:08:37,370
And as I mentioned without
its implementation.

1118
01:08:37,370 --> 01:08:41,029
So you just have the
function itself, and then

1119
01:08:41,029 --> 01:08:43,200
a full documentation.

1120
01:08:43,200 --> 01:08:48,920
So here, you would want the
LLM based on your user query

1121
01:08:48,920 --> 01:08:53,040
to feed the right
arguments to your function.

1122
01:08:53,040 --> 01:08:55,080
s to your point,
the goal of the LLM

1123
01:08:55,080 --> 01:08:59,080
here is not going to be to
infer any of the functions

1124
01:08:59,080 --> 01:09:02,520
implementations, rather
only what arguments we

1125
01:09:02,520 --> 01:09:04,300
should put to it.

1126
01:09:04,300 --> 01:09:04,800
Yeah?

1127
01:09:19,941 --> 01:09:21,899
So the question is, how
do you even train this?

1128
01:09:21,899 --> 01:09:24,920
So we're going to see
that in just a few slides.

1129
01:09:24,920 --> 01:09:25,420
Great point.

1130
01:09:25,420 --> 01:09:28,460
That's the next question
we need to ask ourselves.

1131
01:09:33,840 --> 01:09:38,240
So we're going to see
how we train these.

1132
01:09:38,240 --> 01:09:42,420
But here, let's say
it has been trained.

1133
01:09:42,420 --> 01:09:45,939
The LLM would have, from
its context, probably

1134
01:09:45,939 --> 01:09:48,180
our localization,
because let's say

1135
01:09:48,180 --> 01:09:52,020
you have activated your
location permissions

1136
01:09:52,020 --> 01:09:53,880
and your LLM knows
where you are.

1137
01:09:53,880 --> 01:09:55,820
So it knows you are at Stanford.

1138
01:09:55,820 --> 01:09:58,020
And these would
be the coordinates

1139
01:09:58,020 --> 01:10:00,580
being fed to your LLM.

1140
01:10:00,580 --> 01:10:04,800
And then the second stage is to
actually do that function call.

1141
01:10:04,800 --> 01:10:08,260
So it has nothing
to do with LLMs.

1142
01:10:08,260 --> 01:10:10,940
You just take your
function, your argument,

1143
01:10:10,940 --> 01:10:16,220
and you execute that
and you get some answer.

1144
01:10:16,220 --> 01:10:19,140
And the answer, as we
mentioned, is structured

1145
01:10:19,140 --> 01:10:20,940
in a way that's understandable.

1146
01:10:20,940 --> 01:10:22,900
So in that function
implementation,

1147
01:10:22,900 --> 01:10:28,220
you return some object that
informs characteristics

1148
01:10:28,220 --> 01:10:30,020
about the return teddy bear.

1149
01:10:30,020 --> 01:10:34,900
So for example, you have its
name, maybe location, and so on.

1150
01:10:34,900 --> 01:10:38,940
And you feed that
response back to the LLM

1151
01:10:38,940 --> 01:10:41,760
in order to get
a final response.

1152
01:10:41,760 --> 01:10:45,480
So when you ask to do
LLM a given question,

1153
01:10:45,480 --> 01:10:50,440
you don't want to have this
JSON-like response, but rather

1154
01:10:50,440 --> 01:10:52,520
a response in natural language.

1155
01:10:52,520 --> 01:10:57,840
And this exactly is the
motivation for that last stage.

1156
01:10:57,840 --> 01:10:59,880
So I'm going to pause
here for a second

1157
01:10:59,880 --> 01:11:04,680
and check that this three-stage
mechanism makes sense

1158
01:11:04,680 --> 01:11:05,460
to everyone.

1159
01:11:09,640 --> 01:11:10,140
OK.

1160
01:11:10,140 --> 01:11:11,920
Great.

1161
01:11:11,920 --> 01:11:15,760
And exactly what you
were mentioning here

1162
01:11:15,760 --> 01:11:17,500
is going to be the next focus.

1163
01:11:17,500 --> 01:11:20,140
How do you even train that?

1164
01:11:20,140 --> 01:11:22,800
So let me ask you this question.

1165
01:11:22,800 --> 01:11:27,960
If you were to train an
LLM to use this tool,

1166
01:11:27,960 --> 01:11:29,980
what steps would you
need to focus on?

1167
01:11:36,610 --> 01:11:40,470
So the answer is you're going
to feed the API implementation.

1168
01:11:40,470 --> 01:11:42,130
Yes.

1169
01:11:42,130 --> 01:11:48,210
So you would need the first LLM
call to be somehow recognizing

1170
01:11:48,210 --> 01:11:52,290
the pattern of the function
implementation and the query,

1171
01:11:52,290 --> 01:11:57,170
and link it to the
arguments that you

1172
01:11:57,170 --> 01:11:58,350
would put in your function.

1173
01:11:58,350 --> 01:11:58,850
So yeah.

1174
01:11:58,850 --> 01:11:59,570
Great.

1175
01:11:59,570 --> 01:12:01,730
So tool prediction.

1176
01:12:01,730 --> 01:12:05,040
And do you need a
second set of SFT pairs?

1177
01:12:11,690 --> 01:12:15,290
So you have this last stage
that is still LLM-driven,

1178
01:12:15,290 --> 01:12:18,290
where you have your tool
answer, and you need

1179
01:12:18,290 --> 01:12:19,640
to output a final response.

1180
01:12:22,850 --> 01:12:25,330
You might say, OK,
hey, the LLM has

1181
01:12:25,330 --> 01:12:27,650
seen a bunch of
structured data and knows

1182
01:12:27,650 --> 01:12:30,690
how to put into words,
things that it sees,

1183
01:12:30,690 --> 01:12:32,370
which is a fair point.

1184
01:12:32,370 --> 01:12:35,010
But usually, you might
want your responses

1185
01:12:35,010 --> 01:12:37,510
to be formatted a given way.

1186
01:12:37,510 --> 01:12:40,990
So you might want to
also have SFT pairs that

1187
01:12:40,990 --> 01:12:44,150
do this mapping the
way you want it to.

1188
01:12:44,150 --> 01:12:49,110
So this is why you typically
have these two SFT pairs.

1189
01:12:49,110 --> 01:12:51,790
And if I have to be
a bit more precise,

1190
01:12:51,790 --> 01:12:55,470
the second pair isn't just
mapping the JSON response

1191
01:12:55,470 --> 01:12:57,630
to the final response,
it's actually

1192
01:12:57,630 --> 01:13:00,750
linking all the
conversation history so far,

1193
01:13:00,750 --> 01:13:04,270
so that it knows that the
initial query was someone

1194
01:13:04,270 --> 01:13:06,070
in search of a teddy bear.

1195
01:13:06,070 --> 01:13:07,930
It knows there has
been a tool call,

1196
01:13:07,930 --> 01:13:12,310
and it knows that the results
correspond to that tool call.

1197
01:13:12,310 --> 01:13:18,830
So it would be a slightly
longer input in this SFT pair.

1198
01:13:18,830 --> 01:13:21,690
Does that make sense?

1199
01:13:21,690 --> 01:13:22,190
OK.

1200
01:13:22,190 --> 01:13:22,650
Great.

1201
01:13:22,650 --> 01:13:23,150
Yeah?

1202
01:13:29,750 --> 01:13:30,490
Yeah.

1203
01:13:30,490 --> 01:13:31,210
So great point.

1204
01:13:31,210 --> 01:13:33,780
So the question is, what
if we have more tools,

1205
01:13:33,780 --> 01:13:37,000
do we need some tool
selection or more examples?

1206
01:13:37,000 --> 01:13:38,260
So this is a great topic.

1207
01:13:38,260 --> 01:13:41,980
We're going to see it
like in a few slides.

1208
01:13:41,980 --> 01:13:42,480
Yeah.

1209
01:13:42,480 --> 01:13:45,660
So it's slightly more
complex way of doing things.

1210
01:13:45,660 --> 01:13:49,560
But if you want a very quick
answer, if you go the SFT way,

1211
01:13:49,560 --> 01:13:54,400
you could show
multi-tool inputs.

1212
01:13:54,400 --> 01:13:57,920
So you could include all of
that in your SFT data sets.

1213
01:13:57,920 --> 01:14:03,720
But we're going to see the topic
of tool selection very soon.

1214
01:14:03,720 --> 01:14:04,300
Great.

1215
01:14:04,300 --> 01:14:05,380
Any other questions?

1216
01:14:08,140 --> 01:14:08,640
OK.

1217
01:14:08,640 --> 01:14:11,320
Awesome.

1218
01:14:11,320 --> 01:14:13,480
This is what I just mentioned.

1219
01:14:13,480 --> 01:14:15,200
Yeah, the conversation
history so far

1220
01:14:15,200 --> 01:14:17,860
is always what you get
as part of the input.

1221
01:14:17,860 --> 01:14:20,880
And then the output is what you
would want the LLM to predict

1222
01:14:20,880 --> 01:14:22,680
at that given stage.

1223
01:14:22,680 --> 01:14:24,760
And since you're
doing SFT here, you

1224
01:14:24,760 --> 01:14:29,040
don't have just one, but
multiple such examples.

1225
01:14:29,040 --> 01:14:33,980
And you would want your examples
to be varied and representing

1226
01:14:33,980 --> 01:14:36,500
the typical user distribution.

1227
01:14:36,500 --> 01:14:40,740
So I was asking,
find a bear near me.

1228
01:14:40,740 --> 01:14:43,820
And this example
showed to the model

1229
01:14:43,820 --> 01:14:47,140
how you could ground the
information of location

1230
01:14:47,140 --> 01:14:51,060
based on the user's location,
even though you didn't give it.

1231
01:14:51,060 --> 01:14:54,740
And in this other examples,
you could give the model

1232
01:14:54,740 --> 01:14:57,900
other kinds of instructions,
directly saying,

1233
01:14:57,900 --> 01:15:02,820
I want a bear at that location
to teach the model to look at--

1234
01:15:02,820 --> 01:15:05,980
like to ground the argument
at different places.

1235
01:15:05,980 --> 01:15:09,900
And you could expand
these sets by also

1236
01:15:09,900 --> 01:15:11,820
varying the kind of
input, so it doesn't

1237
01:15:11,820 --> 01:15:13,200
have to be worried that way.

1238
01:15:13,200 --> 01:15:16,700
You could do it multi-turn maybe
in the middle of a conversation,

1239
01:15:16,700 --> 01:15:21,300
you ask for a bear and so on.

1240
01:15:21,300 --> 01:15:21,800
OK.

1241
01:15:21,800 --> 01:15:22,620
Great.

1242
01:15:22,620 --> 01:15:28,340
But this is not the only way
of training a model to do so.

1243
01:15:28,340 --> 01:15:33,840
So these days, LLMs become
more and more powerful

1244
01:15:33,840 --> 01:15:35,320
in their reasoning.

1245
01:15:35,320 --> 01:15:38,760
And the kind of data they
are trained at pre-training

1246
01:15:38,760 --> 01:15:41,480
and initial instruction
tuning is typically

1247
01:15:41,480 --> 01:15:44,000
these kinds of code data.

1248
01:15:44,000 --> 01:15:48,360
So at the end of it, they how
to manipulate Python codes

1249
01:15:48,360 --> 01:15:50,000
very well.

1250
01:15:50,000 --> 01:15:53,720
So you might ask yourself,
is it really needed for me

1251
01:15:53,720 --> 01:16:00,160
to teach the model how to map
a query to a function call?

1252
01:16:00,160 --> 01:16:04,600
And that is a very
interesting observation.

1253
01:16:04,600 --> 01:16:07,960
And you see these
days that you can

1254
01:16:07,960 --> 01:16:13,160
forego of specific SFT training
and try to get around it

1255
01:16:13,160 --> 01:16:15,400
with only training.

1256
01:16:15,400 --> 01:16:24,440
So here, instead of writing SFT
and then retraining the model,

1257
01:16:24,440 --> 01:16:27,530
we're going to see that you
could actually replace it

1258
01:16:27,530 --> 01:16:30,610
with only an explanation.

1259
01:16:30,610 --> 01:16:34,290
And does anyone have an idea
of how we could even come up

1260
01:16:34,290 --> 01:16:35,750
with such an explanation?

1261
01:16:38,930 --> 01:16:41,450
So let's say I have a new tool.

1262
01:16:41,450 --> 01:16:42,830
I have the API.

1263
01:16:42,830 --> 01:16:45,530
I want my model to use it.

1264
01:16:45,530 --> 01:16:46,950
How would you go around it?

1265
01:16:52,570 --> 01:16:54,390
Yeah, that's a great point.

1266
01:16:54,390 --> 01:16:56,550
So one method could
be few shot learning.

1267
01:16:56,550 --> 01:17:02,713
You just show in the context
window samples of input/output.

1268
01:17:02,713 --> 01:17:03,630
This is a great point.

1269
01:17:03,630 --> 01:17:04,838
You could definitely do that.

1270
01:17:04,838 --> 01:17:09,810
And this is typically
one accepted practice.

1271
01:17:09,810 --> 01:17:13,010
But if I told you
that few shot learning

1272
01:17:13,010 --> 01:17:16,950
has challenges when it
comes to generalization,

1273
01:17:16,950 --> 01:17:21,170
because you would need to give
specific points as input/output.

1274
01:17:21,170 --> 01:17:24,368
So it might fit to
some cases and not

1275
01:17:24,368 --> 01:17:25,910
necessarily
unnecessarily generalized

1276
01:17:25,910 --> 01:17:29,510
to the whole span
of human language.

1277
01:17:29,510 --> 01:17:32,130
Is there another way
you could go around it?

1278
01:17:39,530 --> 01:17:40,030
Yeah.

1279
01:17:40,030 --> 01:17:43,090
So the answer is ask
it to do reasoning.

1280
01:17:43,090 --> 01:17:44,750
Great point.

1281
01:17:44,750 --> 01:17:49,950
And writing a prompt that does
the reasoning in a way that

1282
01:17:49,950 --> 01:17:52,470
makes sense is very hard.

1283
01:17:52,470 --> 01:17:55,270
So in practice, you
wouldn't write it yourself.

1284
01:17:55,270 --> 01:17:59,030
You would take these SFT pairs.

1285
01:17:59,030 --> 01:18:02,390
So these are the behavior
that you want to enforce.

1286
01:18:02,390 --> 01:18:05,590
And you could use it
as some evaluation set.

1287
01:18:05,590 --> 01:18:10,310
So you could say, OK, hey,
if I ask this question,

1288
01:18:10,310 --> 01:18:13,350
I want that stool call.

1289
01:18:13,350 --> 01:18:16,030
And you have a set of pairs.

1290
01:18:16,030 --> 01:18:19,350
And you could run
whatever you have

1291
01:18:19,350 --> 01:18:22,550
so far in terms of explanation.

1292
01:18:22,550 --> 01:18:27,110
You evaluate these prompts
against the evaluation set.

1293
01:18:27,110 --> 01:18:28,990
So you have some
wins and losses.

1294
01:18:28,990 --> 01:18:30,910
Maybe find a bear in Paris.

1295
01:18:30,910 --> 01:18:32,330
Doesn't work well.

1296
01:18:32,330 --> 01:18:34,210
Some other prompts do.

1297
01:18:34,210 --> 01:18:40,170
So you have a list of
each sample with a score.

1298
01:18:40,170 --> 01:18:44,650
And you could feed it
back to a reasoning model,

1299
01:18:44,650 --> 01:18:49,010
typically, to do the
explanation writing for you.

1300
01:18:49,010 --> 01:18:56,530
So this is a trick to help you
avoid doing that hard work.

1301
01:18:56,530 --> 01:19:00,590
Basically, showing the model,
hey, with the current prompts,

1302
01:19:00,590 --> 01:19:02,170
here's what we get.

1303
01:19:02,170 --> 01:19:06,090
What would you have changed in
order to make the evaluation

1304
01:19:06,090 --> 01:19:07,410
results better?

1305
01:19:07,410 --> 01:19:10,250
So you get with that
process an iteration

1306
01:19:10,250 --> 01:19:12,630
on the detailed explanation.

1307
01:19:12,630 --> 01:19:14,630
And if you have to see
results in practice,

1308
01:19:14,630 --> 01:19:17,170
you would be surprised
at how well it

1309
01:19:17,170 --> 01:19:19,130
does the explanation for you.

1310
01:19:19,130 --> 01:19:23,180
So the takeaway here
is I do not recommend

1311
01:19:23,180 --> 01:19:24,920
you write it end-to-end.

1312
01:19:24,920 --> 01:19:29,380
Maybe just a draft and you
let some very powerful model

1313
01:19:29,380 --> 01:19:35,880
with excellent knowledge
of logic do it for you.

1314
01:19:35,880 --> 01:19:36,380
Yeah?

1315
01:19:51,140 --> 01:19:51,640
Yeah.

1316
01:19:51,640 --> 01:19:53,680
So the question is,
what you just mentioned,

1317
01:19:53,680 --> 01:19:55,360
is it training or inference?

1318
01:19:55,360 --> 01:19:56,780
So it's training.

1319
01:19:56,780 --> 01:19:58,720
So you do it at
the very beginning.

1320
01:19:58,720 --> 01:20:02,300
You want a fixed prompt
that explains to the LLM

1321
01:20:02,300 --> 01:20:04,720
how to use it, how
to use that function.

1322
01:20:04,720 --> 01:20:06,900
So you would typically
do that offline.

1323
01:20:06,900 --> 01:20:09,500
Offline you iterate
on the explanation

1324
01:20:09,500 --> 01:20:12,780
that says exactly how
you use the prompt, how

1325
01:20:12,780 --> 01:20:14,740
you use the function.

1326
01:20:14,740 --> 01:20:18,300
And then at inference time, you
would put that fixed explanation

1327
01:20:18,300 --> 01:20:21,720
alongside the function API,
such that for any query,

1328
01:20:21,720 --> 01:20:24,715
it knows what to do.

1329
01:20:24,715 --> 01:20:25,590
Does that make sense?

1330
01:20:28,040 --> 01:20:28,540
OK.

1331
01:20:28,540 --> 01:20:30,480
Great.

1332
01:20:30,480 --> 01:20:32,140
Any other questions here?

1333
01:20:35,060 --> 01:20:35,560
OK.

1334
01:20:35,560 --> 01:20:36,060
Amazing.

1335
01:20:38,680 --> 01:20:41,640
I just mentioned an
example with teddy bears

1336
01:20:41,640 --> 01:20:45,620
that would be in the category
of maybe informational.

1337
01:20:48,320 --> 01:20:51,720
So you have a question and you
want to ask some external API

1338
01:20:51,720 --> 01:20:53,480
to retrieve that.

1339
01:20:53,480 --> 01:20:56,160
And you have in reality
a lot more use cases

1340
01:20:56,160 --> 01:20:57,140
that you might see.

1341
01:20:57,140 --> 01:21:00,940
So one actually mentioned,
you have some cutoff dates.

1342
01:21:00,940 --> 01:21:04,680
And let's say you ask your
LLM about news of the day.

1343
01:21:04,680 --> 01:21:07,240
So you typically wouldn't
have anything that

1344
01:21:07,240 --> 01:21:08,740
comes from the model itself.

1345
01:21:08,740 --> 01:21:12,880
You would have an API that
fetches it from a tool called

1346
01:21:12,880 --> 01:21:15,360
maybe Search.

1347
01:21:15,360 --> 01:21:17,420
But you have also
other kinds of tools

1348
01:21:17,420 --> 01:21:20,400
available in the
information category.

1349
01:21:20,400 --> 01:21:25,180
So for example,
whether stocks and,

1350
01:21:25,180 --> 01:21:30,060
let's see, but you also
have other categories.

1351
01:21:30,060 --> 01:21:33,660
For example, if you
want to ask the model to

1352
01:21:33,660 --> 01:21:36,120
do some calculation for you.

1353
01:21:36,120 --> 01:21:38,380
You could let the
model figure it out

1354
01:21:38,380 --> 01:21:40,060
with some reasoning chain.

1355
01:21:40,060 --> 01:21:45,420
But one way to get around
it is to transform the query

1356
01:21:45,420 --> 01:21:51,540
into code, execute that code,
and then read out the answer.

1357
01:21:51,540 --> 01:21:57,060
So this is why tool call has
a whole span of applications

1358
01:21:57,060 --> 01:22:01,020
in the computation area.

1359
01:22:01,020 --> 01:22:02,740
So you have calculations.

1360
01:22:02,740 --> 01:22:06,520
And you have another category
that we can cite here.

1361
01:22:06,520 --> 01:22:10,220
So you can take actions
on behalf of the user.

1362
01:22:10,220 --> 01:22:13,080
So let's say you have a
tool that sends emails.

1363
01:22:13,080 --> 01:22:17,070
You could ask the model
to send an email for you,

1364
01:22:17,070 --> 01:22:19,990
and it could put
the right things

1365
01:22:19,990 --> 01:22:25,470
into the header and the message
body, and even hit Send for you

1366
01:22:25,470 --> 01:22:27,630
because you have
that component that

1367
01:22:27,630 --> 01:22:33,810
interacts with the external
world as part of the tool API.

1368
01:22:33,810 --> 01:22:34,310
Yeah.

1369
01:22:34,310 --> 01:22:35,890
So these are just
a few examples,

1370
01:22:35,890 --> 01:22:39,350
but I just want to say that
the field of tool calling

1371
01:22:39,350 --> 01:22:40,370
is so powerful.

1372
01:22:40,370 --> 01:22:43,230
You can do anything you want.

1373
01:22:43,230 --> 01:22:47,670
And in practice, exactly
as you mentioned,

1374
01:22:47,670 --> 01:22:53,630
you wouldn't have just a single
tool API as part of the context.

1375
01:22:53,630 --> 01:22:57,430
You would have several ones
because your LLM is not just

1376
01:22:57,430 --> 01:22:59,730
an LLM for finding bears.

1377
01:22:59,730 --> 01:23:02,430
You might want to do other
things with your LLM.

1378
01:23:02,430 --> 01:23:05,430
Maybe you want to
hug a teddy bear

1379
01:23:05,430 --> 01:23:09,270
or check a teddy bear's
moods, send teddy bear's

1380
01:23:09,270 --> 01:23:11,790
a gift and other things.

1381
01:23:11,790 --> 01:23:15,570
So you have a lot
more functions that

1382
01:23:15,570 --> 01:23:18,770
might be relevant to
be added as a preamble.

1383
01:23:18,770 --> 01:23:23,050
Just because you don't know what
function would need to be used,

1384
01:23:23,050 --> 01:23:25,180
you just need to put all
of that just in case.

1385
01:23:28,028 --> 01:23:29,570
The setup is exactly
the one that you

1386
01:23:29,570 --> 01:23:33,560
mentioned where you don't have
just one API but multiple ones.

1387
01:23:36,250 --> 01:23:40,550
Does anyone see any
issues with doing so?

1388
01:23:43,650 --> 01:23:46,130
So the suggestion is that,
that's a lot of tools.

1389
01:23:46,130 --> 01:23:47,270
And then you're right.

1390
01:23:47,270 --> 01:23:49,450
So typically, if you
have too many tools,

1391
01:23:49,450 --> 01:23:51,690
you have the problem
that Afshine mentioned

1392
01:23:51,690 --> 01:23:54,070
at the beginning of a
needle in a haystack,

1393
01:23:54,070 --> 01:23:58,010
where maybe some tool API
will get lost in the context

1394
01:23:58,010 --> 01:24:00,130
and you don't
really what to use.

1395
01:24:00,130 --> 01:24:04,370
You have a lot of
conflicting APIs, maybe,

1396
01:24:04,370 --> 01:24:11,400
and we're going to see very
soon how to overcome that issue.

1397
01:24:11,400 --> 01:24:11,900
OK.

1398
01:24:11,900 --> 01:24:13,220
Great.

1399
01:24:13,220 --> 01:24:19,540
So I want to take a pause here
and summarize how far we've come

1400
01:24:19,540 --> 01:24:23,100
and some of the
drawbacks that we have

1401
01:24:23,100 --> 01:24:27,500
and see together what we could
do to remedy these drawbacks.

1402
01:24:27,500 --> 01:24:31,420
So first, we saw that
we came from an LLM that

1403
01:24:31,420 --> 01:24:35,460
just responded back at
you with a normal words.

1404
01:24:35,460 --> 01:24:40,000
To an LLM that can actually
interact with the outside world,

1405
01:24:40,000 --> 01:24:44,100
fetch real-time
information, or even extends

1406
01:24:44,100 --> 01:24:47,380
computing capabilities.

1407
01:24:47,380 --> 01:24:51,380
And exactly like
overcomes the issue

1408
01:24:51,380 --> 01:24:54,020
that Afshine was mentioning
the knowledge cutoff

1409
01:24:54,020 --> 01:24:58,980
one in a different way that
than what RAG would do.

1410
01:24:58,980 --> 01:25:03,700
So you could see these two
methods as being complementary.

1411
01:25:03,700 --> 01:25:08,180
And yeah, both try to do the
same thing in some sense.

1412
01:25:08,180 --> 01:25:14,320
But exactly as someone mentioned
here, if you have more tools,

1413
01:25:14,320 --> 01:25:17,880
then your context
window might have things

1414
01:25:17,880 --> 01:25:19,940
that it doesn't need.

1415
01:25:19,940 --> 01:25:23,680
And then if you try to
support so many cases,

1416
01:25:23,680 --> 01:25:27,560
you might end up being
mediocre at all of them.

1417
01:25:27,560 --> 01:25:30,480
So this is an issue.

1418
01:25:30,480 --> 01:25:32,720
And even if that
wasn't an issue,

1419
01:25:32,720 --> 01:25:36,040
you still have the context
window that is finite.

1420
01:25:36,040 --> 01:25:39,080
So let's say you have
hundreds of millions

1421
01:25:39,080 --> 01:25:42,600
of users that use
your LLM and that want

1422
01:25:42,600 --> 01:25:44,800
to use to do a lot of things.

1423
01:25:44,800 --> 01:25:47,880
You cannot support
everyone's use cases at once,

1424
01:25:47,880 --> 01:25:52,160
just because you couldn't
possibly fit all of such tools

1425
01:25:52,160 --> 01:25:52,870
in your context.

1426
01:25:55,640 --> 01:26:00,880
And then last, when I
mentioned these tools,

1427
01:26:00,880 --> 01:26:03,920
these are things I hand wrote.

1428
01:26:03,920 --> 01:26:08,580
And maybe each LLM has their own
way of defining and using tools.

1429
01:26:08,580 --> 01:26:11,160
We're going to see if there
is a way to standardize,

1430
01:26:11,160 --> 01:26:16,420
maybe the way we define
and use tools later on.

1431
01:26:16,420 --> 01:26:19,780
So do these
drawbacks make sense.

1432
01:26:19,780 --> 01:26:20,700
Yeah.

1433
01:26:20,700 --> 01:26:21,200
OK.

1434
01:26:21,200 --> 01:26:22,340
Great.

1435
01:26:22,340 --> 01:26:26,340
So let's move on
to tool selection.

1436
01:26:26,340 --> 01:26:29,540
So let's see what
we could do in order

1437
01:26:29,540 --> 01:26:34,140
to make a tool
use more scalable.

1438
01:26:34,140 --> 01:26:39,820
So I'm going to cite
here a technical paper

1439
01:26:39,820 --> 01:26:45,060
from Google DeepMind, which
uses a tool selector system.

1440
01:26:45,060 --> 01:26:47,980
So it functions in two steps.

1441
01:26:47,980 --> 01:26:51,540
So first you have
your query and you

1442
01:26:51,540 --> 01:26:55,740
have a list of tools that
can be as big as you want.

1443
01:26:55,740 --> 01:26:58,540
And a list of
tools only contains

1444
01:26:58,540 --> 01:27:03,740
the API name and, maybe one or
two words about what it does.

1445
01:27:03,740 --> 01:27:08,350
So you have this prompt
and the list of tools.

1446
01:27:08,350 --> 01:27:15,190
And we ask the LLM to pick the
tools that might be relevant.

1447
01:27:15,190 --> 01:27:20,110
So this is why the technical
paper calls this system tool

1448
01:27:20,110 --> 01:27:21,270
selector.

1449
01:27:21,270 --> 01:27:25,870
You could even see
the term router being

1450
01:27:25,870 --> 01:27:27,330
pronounced in the literature.

1451
01:27:27,330 --> 01:27:31,270
So tool selection, routing
are similar concepts.

1452
01:27:31,270 --> 01:27:35,550
And the goal here is to
restrict the number of tools

1453
01:27:35,550 --> 01:27:38,550
to only those that
might be useful.

1454
01:27:38,550 --> 01:27:43,590
And in the second stage, you
take all the selected tool APIs

1455
01:27:43,590 --> 01:27:48,910
and feed only those to the
context alongside your query.

1456
01:27:48,910 --> 01:27:52,190
And this is one
way you could take

1457
01:27:52,190 --> 01:27:58,520
to overcome this issue of
having too many tools at once.

1458
01:28:01,110 --> 01:28:04,290
Is everyone convinced that tool
selection could be a good way

1459
01:28:04,290 --> 01:28:07,230
to fix the problem here?

1460
01:28:14,690 --> 01:28:16,650
So the question is
that basically RAG?

1461
01:28:16,650 --> 01:28:17,890
You could do it with RAG.

1462
01:28:17,890 --> 01:28:19,230
That's a great point.

1463
01:28:19,230 --> 01:28:21,330
But it doesn't
necessarily have to.

1464
01:28:21,330 --> 01:28:27,050
So you could have an LLM
that does this job, just

1465
01:28:27,050 --> 01:28:29,350
picking the right tools.

1466
01:28:29,350 --> 01:28:31,730
And you ask some
instructions to the LLM

1467
01:28:31,730 --> 01:28:33,350
to output the right answer.

1468
01:28:33,350 --> 01:28:35,690
You could definitely
do it with RAG.

1469
01:28:35,690 --> 01:28:36,990
That is just a great point.

1470
01:28:36,990 --> 01:28:37,490
Yeah.

1471
01:28:40,930 --> 01:28:43,710
So does it make
sense to everyone?

1472
01:28:43,710 --> 01:28:44,210
OK.

1473
01:28:44,210 --> 01:28:45,030
Great.

1474
01:28:45,030 --> 01:28:47,190
And I see time is flying.

1475
01:28:47,190 --> 01:28:52,650
So we're going to go very
quickly on the standardization

1476
01:28:52,650 --> 01:28:53,570
issue.

1477
01:28:53,570 --> 01:28:57,370
So as I mentioned, every
tools implementation,

1478
01:28:57,370 --> 01:29:00,490
like the way you specify
a tool implementation

1479
01:29:00,490 --> 01:29:03,050
can be bespoke to a given LLM.

1480
01:29:03,050 --> 01:29:04,750
And you wouldn't want that.

1481
01:29:04,750 --> 01:29:07,830
Because for every
LLM, you might need

1482
01:29:07,830 --> 01:29:14,150
to implement always these
tools over and over again.

1483
01:29:14,150 --> 01:29:17,190
And duplication is
not what you want.

1484
01:29:17,190 --> 01:29:19,990
This is why there is
a standard called MCP,

1485
01:29:19,990 --> 01:29:24,750
that I know a lot of
people talk about it.

1486
01:29:24,750 --> 01:29:28,510
So it's something from
the Anthropic team

1487
01:29:28,510 --> 01:29:34,130
that standardizes the way
tools are exposed to models.

1488
01:29:34,130 --> 01:29:35,010
So it's a protocol.

1489
01:29:35,010 --> 01:29:37,550
It's called a model
context protocol.

1490
01:29:37,550 --> 01:29:43,350
And it defines a standard way
of presenting these tools.

1491
01:29:43,350 --> 01:29:49,710
So I'm going just to say
the very big lines of it,

1492
01:29:49,710 --> 01:29:53,070
so you have this kind of
vocabulary as part of MCP.

1493
01:29:53,070 --> 01:29:56,870
So you have an MCP
server, which is

1494
01:29:56,870 --> 01:30:01,960
the instance that serves tools.

1495
01:30:01,960 --> 01:30:05,760
And then tools are
implementations of the functions

1496
01:30:05,760 --> 01:30:07,920
that you want people to use.

1497
01:30:07,920 --> 01:30:12,800
Prompts are templates that
could show the user how

1498
01:30:12,800 --> 01:30:15,000
to use these tools.

1499
01:30:15,000 --> 01:30:18,520
And then all of these
can anchor on resources,

1500
01:30:18,520 --> 01:30:23,040
which are external
databases that you

1501
01:30:23,040 --> 01:30:25,800
can use to complete the task.

1502
01:30:25,800 --> 01:30:29,200
And then an MCP server,
when you use it,

1503
01:30:29,200 --> 01:30:31,320
has a one-to-one
connection with a piece

1504
01:30:31,320 --> 01:30:35,880
of infrastructure in your LLM
host that is called MCP clients.

1505
01:30:35,880 --> 01:30:39,000
But these are maybe
infrastructure details.

1506
01:30:39,000 --> 01:30:43,080
And I just want to ground what
I just mentioned in reality.

1507
01:30:43,080 --> 01:30:47,480
So we know our teddy bear
loves to read poetry.

1508
01:30:47,480 --> 01:30:52,540
So in the case of recommending
a poetry book to our teddy bear,

1509
01:30:52,540 --> 01:30:55,760
you could think of a
MCP server that provides

1510
01:30:55,760 --> 01:30:59,780
tools that are linked to books.

1511
01:30:59,780 --> 01:31:02,080
So your LLM hosts here--

1512
01:31:02,080 --> 01:31:04,100
so let's just take
the example of Claude

1513
01:31:04,100 --> 01:31:06,580
since MCP is from Anthropic.

1514
01:31:06,580 --> 01:31:09,460
So Claude would
be your LLM host.

1515
01:31:09,460 --> 01:31:13,940
Your MCP server would
be probably implemented

1516
01:31:13,940 --> 01:31:15,060
by your book provider.

1517
01:31:15,060 --> 01:31:17,220
Because typically, they
are the most experts

1518
01:31:17,220 --> 01:31:19,940
as at serving such content.

1519
01:31:19,940 --> 01:31:23,420
And we could assume that
the book provider, MCP

1520
01:31:23,420 --> 01:31:28,460
server has tools regarding
finding books or recommending

1521
01:31:28,460 --> 01:31:28,960
them.

1522
01:31:28,960 --> 01:31:33,900
And then the prompts here
could be a ways to show you

1523
01:31:33,900 --> 01:31:36,540
how to find a given
title, or maybe

1524
01:31:36,540 --> 01:31:39,780
recommend it with respect to
some flavor, maybe with respect

1525
01:31:39,780 --> 01:31:42,180
to the user's test taste.

1526
01:31:42,180 --> 01:31:44,380
And some examples
of resources here

1527
01:31:44,380 --> 01:31:48,100
could be the teddy bear's
personal collection,

1528
01:31:48,100 --> 01:31:55,280
or maybe top books that people
buy, just as an example.

1529
01:31:55,280 --> 01:31:55,780
OK.

1530
01:31:55,780 --> 01:31:56,840
Awesome.

1531
01:31:56,840 --> 01:31:59,640
So now, I'm going to
come to potentially

1532
01:31:59,640 --> 01:32:03,660
the most exciting part
of today's lecture,

1533
01:32:03,660 --> 01:32:05,520
which is agents.

1534
01:32:05,520 --> 01:32:11,680
So we saw how much more powerful
LLMs could become with tools.

1535
01:32:11,680 --> 01:32:16,960
Agents could be seen as
one layer up from it.

1536
01:32:16,960 --> 01:32:21,080
So I'm going to give
first a definition,

1537
01:32:21,080 --> 01:32:25,640
just so that we agree of
what agent means here.

1538
01:32:25,640 --> 01:32:28,360
So it's a system that
autonomously pursues

1539
01:32:28,360 --> 01:32:32,520
goal and completes tasks
on a user's behalf.

1540
01:32:32,520 --> 01:32:41,040
So compared to tools, you
not only can perform tasks,

1541
01:32:41,040 --> 01:32:44,840
but you have also some
reasoning involved in it.

1542
01:32:44,840 --> 01:32:47,840
So you could have multiple
loops of iterations.

1543
01:32:47,840 --> 01:32:50,800
And this is what
differentiates an agent

1544
01:32:50,800 --> 01:32:53,720
from a tool in plain terms.

1545
01:32:53,720 --> 01:32:55,790
When usually people
talk about agents,

1546
01:32:55,790 --> 01:33:02,970
it has that recurrence or
higher level of reasoning baked

1547
01:33:02,970 --> 01:33:04,730
into it.

1548
01:33:04,730 --> 01:33:09,530
And so I'm going to contrast
like the agentic world

1549
01:33:09,530 --> 01:33:10,930
with respect to
the world we have

1550
01:33:10,930 --> 01:33:17,290
seen, where you may have
multiple calls to tools.

1551
01:33:17,290 --> 01:33:20,770
And these new agentic
framework is not

1552
01:33:20,770 --> 01:33:25,950
necessarily disjoint from the
ones that we presented before.

1553
01:33:25,950 --> 01:33:30,150
You could well have reasoning
chains inside of it.

1554
01:33:30,150 --> 01:33:32,610
So it's like a
potentially overlapping.

1555
01:33:32,610 --> 01:33:41,310
But the structure consists
of tool calls and iterations.

1556
01:33:41,310 --> 01:33:41,810
OK.

1557
01:33:41,810 --> 01:33:43,090
Great.

1558
01:33:43,090 --> 01:33:50,210
And now, I'm going to talk about
a hallmark paper called ReAct,

1559
01:33:50,210 --> 01:33:56,030
to reason plus acts, which
decomposes possible loops

1560
01:33:56,030 --> 01:33:58,510
into different stages.

1561
01:33:58,510 --> 01:34:03,390
So very oftentimes, when you
have a query and you want

1562
01:34:03,390 --> 01:34:07,710
to pursue a goal, you
cannot do it one shot.

1563
01:34:07,710 --> 01:34:10,830
You need somehow to
decompose the goal

1564
01:34:10,830 --> 01:34:16,270
into actionable substeps,
perform each of these steps,

1565
01:34:16,270 --> 01:34:18,230
and then come up
with the answer.

1566
01:34:18,230 --> 01:34:21,170
And this is exactly
what ReAct is about.

1567
01:34:21,170 --> 01:34:28,070
It's about decomposing complex
tasks into loops of things

1568
01:34:28,070 --> 01:34:31,630
that can be done atomically.

1569
01:34:31,630 --> 01:34:34,510
So here, I just want
to say one thing.

1570
01:34:34,510 --> 01:34:40,030
We decompose these steps
into observe, plan, and act.

1571
01:34:40,030 --> 01:34:42,510
But it doesn't necessarily
have to be called that way

1572
01:34:42,510 --> 01:34:43,950
or be in that order.

1573
01:34:43,950 --> 01:34:45,950
For example, the
ReAct paper, I think,

1574
01:34:45,950 --> 01:34:52,980
introduces terms
think, observe, act.

1575
01:34:52,980 --> 01:34:55,520
You might see the language
changing a bit from paper

1576
01:34:55,520 --> 01:34:56,660
to paper to paper.

1577
01:34:56,660 --> 01:35:02,160
But the high-level
intuition remains.

1578
01:35:02,160 --> 01:35:06,600
So let's just ground on
a very specific example.

1579
01:35:06,600 --> 01:35:11,890
So to be in the theme
of these days weather,

1580
01:35:11,890 --> 01:35:13,960
it starts becoming a bit cold.

1581
01:35:13,960 --> 01:35:17,720
And our teddy bear might
be cold in its home.

1582
01:35:17,720 --> 01:35:20,920
So let's just have
that as an input.

1583
01:35:20,920 --> 01:35:22,380
My teddy bear is cold.

1584
01:35:22,380 --> 01:35:24,000
Please, do something.

1585
01:35:24,000 --> 01:35:28,920
And let's see what an agentic
workflow could do about it.

1586
01:35:28,920 --> 01:35:31,700
So first, you have
this observe stage,

1587
01:35:31,700 --> 01:35:38,440
which translates the user query
into an actionable formulation.

1588
01:35:38,440 --> 01:35:40,920
So when you say that
your teddy bear is cold

1589
01:35:40,920 --> 01:35:44,120
and you ask it to do
something like here,

1590
01:35:44,120 --> 01:35:47,880
in this observe stage,
you would link it back

1591
01:35:47,880 --> 01:35:50,900
to the notion of temperature.

1592
01:35:50,900 --> 01:35:52,620
The user's teddy
bear is cold, which

1593
01:35:52,620 --> 01:35:55,300
may be due to the current
temperature of the room, which

1594
01:35:55,300 --> 01:35:57,100
is currently unknown.

1595
01:35:57,100 --> 01:36:00,600
So right off the
bat, you now know

1596
01:36:00,600 --> 01:36:03,740
that you need to do
something with temperatures.

1597
01:36:03,740 --> 01:36:06,300
So this brings us
to the next step

1598
01:36:06,300 --> 01:36:10,420
called Plan, where that
something is unknown,

1599
01:36:10,420 --> 01:36:12,560
and you need to find it.

1600
01:36:12,560 --> 01:36:15,300
Plan will spell
that out for you.

1601
01:36:15,300 --> 01:36:18,900
So here, you want to determine
the temperature of the room.

1602
01:36:18,900 --> 01:36:22,100
And luckily, among
your tools, you

1603
01:36:22,100 --> 01:36:25,120
might have something that
does something in these lines.

1604
01:36:25,120 --> 01:36:26,840
And this is where you use it.

1605
01:36:26,840 --> 01:36:30,620
So the Act stage is
using all these APIs

1606
01:36:30,620 --> 01:36:32,000
that might be in the context.

1607
01:36:32,000 --> 01:36:35,740
So for example here, if you have
get current room temperature,

1608
01:36:35,740 --> 01:36:38,260
this is the way to use it.

1609
01:36:38,260 --> 01:36:43,460
And as I mentioned, these
tools are useful to the LLM

1610
01:36:43,460 --> 01:36:47,680
when you output information back
to it that it can interpret.

1611
01:36:47,680 --> 01:36:51,280
So this tool returns
the temperature.

1612
01:36:51,280 --> 01:36:56,160
And you need now to interpret
what the temperature means.

1613
01:36:56,160 --> 01:36:58,930
So this is why you go back
to the observed stage.

1614
01:37:02,300 --> 01:37:04,967
You describe what
the world looks like

1615
01:37:04,967 --> 01:37:06,300
and what you should do about it.

1616
01:37:06,300 --> 01:37:10,220
So here, you can read that the
temperature of the room is cold.

1617
01:37:10,220 --> 01:37:14,560
It's 65 Fahrenheit,
and the observed stage

1618
01:37:14,560 --> 01:37:19,040
might indicate that it's
colder than expected.

1619
01:37:19,040 --> 01:37:22,800
So this is why you
need to plan something.

1620
01:37:22,800 --> 01:37:25,100
And then at the Plan
stage, you're like this,

1621
01:37:25,100 --> 01:37:27,280
this was colder than expected.

1622
01:37:27,280 --> 01:37:30,000
So I need to increase
the temperature.

1623
01:37:30,000 --> 01:37:32,586
And then you go back
to the Act stage.

1624
01:37:32,586 --> 01:37:35,360
Luckily, how to increase
the temperature.

1625
01:37:35,360 --> 01:37:41,400
And it has a function that can
have the temperature increase

1626
01:37:41,400 --> 01:37:46,610
arguments and put it to it, so
you can adjust the temperature.

1627
01:37:46,610 --> 01:37:51,970
And then once it's
done, the observed stage

1628
01:37:51,970 --> 01:37:55,010
concludes that the
temperature is not

1629
01:37:55,010 --> 01:37:58,970
set to the correct temperature.

1630
01:37:58,970 --> 01:38:01,970
And this is the time where
you can exit the loop

1631
01:38:01,970 --> 01:38:03,600
and return the
response to the user.

1632
01:38:06,210 --> 01:38:10,110
So here, we have increased
the temperature by 5 degrees.

1633
01:38:10,110 --> 01:38:13,730
And then the output reads that
back to the user in the hope

1634
01:38:13,730 --> 01:38:18,290
that it has fulfilled
the user's query.

1635
01:38:18,290 --> 01:38:23,530
So what I described
within the loop

1636
01:38:23,530 --> 01:38:26,850
is what makes a
workflow an agentic one.

1637
01:38:26,850 --> 01:38:28,850
So you have some initial query.

1638
01:38:28,850 --> 01:38:32,210
You have some actions
that you can perform.

1639
01:38:32,210 --> 01:38:34,770
And then at each
stage, the LLM tries

1640
01:38:34,770 --> 01:38:39,370
to see if it has
reached the goal yet.

1641
01:38:39,370 --> 01:38:43,750
And then if it has, then it
will go to the output stage.

1642
01:38:43,750 --> 01:38:47,590
Otherwise, it may have
more reasoning loops,

1643
01:38:47,590 --> 01:38:51,830
where it does more work.

1644
01:38:51,830 --> 01:38:55,300
So does the definition of agent
that I propose here make sense?

1645
01:39:00,190 --> 01:39:00,690
OK.

1646
01:39:00,690 --> 01:39:01,330
Great.

1647
01:39:01,330 --> 01:39:03,870
So now taking this
a bit further,

1648
01:39:03,870 --> 01:39:07,010
you could think of way
more than one agent.

1649
01:39:07,010 --> 01:39:10,910
You could have an agent
for setting the thermostat.

1650
01:39:10,910 --> 01:39:13,590
But maybe in your home,
you want to manage

1651
01:39:13,590 --> 01:39:18,170
how energy is distributed,
or air quality,

1652
01:39:18,170 --> 01:39:20,870
if you have some
settings to tune.

1653
01:39:20,870 --> 01:39:23,190
So you can have
different agents.

1654
01:39:23,190 --> 01:39:27,590
And one interesting use case is
to have the user say something

1655
01:39:27,590 --> 01:39:30,870
to an agent, and
potentially have all of them

1656
01:39:30,870 --> 01:39:33,150
communicate together.

1657
01:39:33,150 --> 01:39:41,450
So these prompts potential
needs for also a standardization

1658
01:39:41,450 --> 01:39:45,450
of communications
between agents,

1659
01:39:45,450 --> 01:39:50,290
similarly to what we have seen
between LLM hosts and tools.

1660
01:39:50,290 --> 01:39:52,770
And this is what prompted
Google to release

1661
01:39:52,770 --> 01:39:57,450
the Agent2Agent protocol
earlier this year.

1662
01:39:57,450 --> 01:40:02,050
So yeah, highly recommend
taking a look at their document

1663
01:40:02,050 --> 01:40:03,070
specification.

1664
01:40:03,070 --> 01:40:08,222
But just to give the
main lines around it,

1665
01:40:08,222 --> 01:40:12,030
you have some standardization
of what an agent can expose.

1666
01:40:12,030 --> 01:40:15,090
So it typically exposes
a set of skills.

1667
01:40:15,090 --> 01:40:18,570
So it can do things.

1668
01:40:18,570 --> 01:40:20,850
And then it gives
examples about it

1669
01:40:20,850 --> 01:40:23,890
so that other agents
are aware of it.

1670
01:40:23,890 --> 01:40:27,050
And what you need
to do as a developer

1671
01:40:27,050 --> 01:40:29,570
would be to define these skills.

1672
01:40:29,570 --> 01:40:35,810
And also, another key thing is
to define how the agent executes

1673
01:40:35,810 --> 01:40:36,990
a given request.

1674
01:40:36,990 --> 01:40:40,900
So for example, when you
execute a given query,

1675
01:40:40,900 --> 01:40:44,540
what is the status that
you emit to other agents?

1676
01:40:44,540 --> 01:40:47,420
Or there is a cancel
method, as well,

1677
01:40:47,420 --> 01:40:50,700
where let's say an agent
says, stop what you're doing.

1678
01:40:50,700 --> 01:40:53,820
What is the process
to cancel an action?

1679
01:40:53,820 --> 01:40:58,780
So these are some of
the main functions

1680
01:40:58,780 --> 01:41:04,240
like the Agent2Agent protocol
asks people to fill out.

1681
01:41:04,240 --> 01:41:04,740
Yeah?

1682
01:41:14,100 --> 01:41:19,140
So the question is, is each
agent an LLM with some context

1683
01:41:19,140 --> 01:41:19,960
to do some tasks?

1684
01:41:19,960 --> 01:41:25,980
So you could definitely
imagine it be the case.

1685
01:41:25,980 --> 01:41:29,740
Typically, in the example
that I mentioned here, yes.

1686
01:41:29,740 --> 01:41:32,800
And the agents
operate independently.

1687
01:41:32,800 --> 01:41:34,780
So they have their
own reasoning loops.

1688
01:41:34,780 --> 01:41:38,930
And all the other agency
is the input and output.

1689
01:41:51,980 --> 01:41:52,480
Yeah.

1690
01:41:52,480 --> 01:41:56,600
So the remark here is
maybe your token budget

1691
01:41:56,600 --> 01:41:59,320
can go all over the place.

1692
01:41:59,320 --> 01:42:02,860
So you can have some budget
restrictions put in place.

1693
01:42:02,860 --> 01:42:04,600
This is a good point.

1694
01:42:04,600 --> 01:42:06,600
But each of these
agents, they would not

1695
01:42:06,600 --> 01:42:08,520
eat on each other's budgets.

1696
01:42:08,520 --> 01:42:11,140
It might eat on
your money budget,

1697
01:42:11,140 --> 01:42:15,480
but this is indeed a concern.

1698
01:42:15,480 --> 01:42:21,000
So I'm going to move on to
the topic of safety, which

1699
01:42:21,000 --> 01:42:23,020
I have not mentioned so far.

1700
01:42:23,020 --> 01:42:25,880
But that is very
important because with

1701
01:42:25,880 --> 01:42:29,080
these new capabilities
comes a whole string

1702
01:42:29,080 --> 01:42:32,000
of new potential issues.

1703
01:42:32,000 --> 01:42:34,860
And you have seen these models.

1704
01:42:34,860 --> 01:42:38,420
They have now the ability
to execute actions for you.

1705
01:42:38,420 --> 01:42:43,140
So you could think of some
harmful actor doing things

1706
01:42:43,140 --> 01:42:45,220
that you wouldn't want for you.

1707
01:42:45,220 --> 01:42:48,980
And I give one example here
that could be a concern--

1708
01:42:48,980 --> 01:42:50,940
data exfiltration.

1709
01:42:50,940 --> 01:42:55,940
So let's say you have access
to a tool that can write

1710
01:42:55,940 --> 01:43:00,260
in a public visible way data.

1711
01:43:00,260 --> 01:43:05,220
So let's say you have, I
don't know some email agent.

1712
01:43:05,220 --> 01:43:08,740
So if you have a prompt that,
for example, says, write

1713
01:43:08,740 --> 01:43:11,860
my password, which potentially
the tool could have access

1714
01:43:11,860 --> 01:43:14,860
to to an email to
that address, you

1715
01:43:14,860 --> 01:43:19,900
could exfiltrate data that
belongs to the user out of it.

1716
01:43:19,900 --> 01:43:23,380
So this is typically one
risk that you might have.

1717
01:43:23,380 --> 01:43:26,320
You can have other safety risks.

1718
01:43:26,320 --> 01:43:29,820
And I link the paper here that
goes through some of them.

1719
01:43:29,820 --> 01:43:32,180
So tool sort.

1720
01:43:32,180 --> 01:43:33,580
So I recommend a read.

1721
01:43:36,590 --> 01:43:39,730
Now, you might ask, what
could you do to get around it?

1722
01:43:39,730 --> 01:43:44,150
So you have typically two
classes of remediations.

1723
01:43:44,150 --> 01:43:46,190
One that might come
at the training

1724
01:43:46,190 --> 01:43:52,630
stage where, if you recall
the training process of R1

1725
01:43:52,630 --> 01:43:58,990
or even other models, you have
these harmlessness components.

1726
01:43:58,990 --> 01:44:03,550
So you typically have data
as part of the data mixtures

1727
